WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.208 --> 00:00:25.356

2
00:00:26.659 --> 00:00:28.970
Michael Jackson's L.A. Residence
June 25. 2009

3
00:01:23.511 --> 00:01:26.555
I arrived at the hospital

4
00:01:26.639 --> 00:01:27.681
Frank Dileo
JACKSON'S MANAGER 1984-89. 2009

5
00:01:27.807 --> 00:01:29.725
and the lady came out
maybe 20 minutes later. a nurse.

6
00:01:31.019 --> 00:01:33.812
I stood up. She said.
"Who are you?"

7
00:01:35.023 --> 00:01:37.733
"I'm Frank Dileo. I manage Michael.

8
00:01:37.817 --> 00:01:39.193
"Is he okay?"

9
00:01:39.277 --> 00:01:42.029
She hesitated. and I knew.

10
00:01:42.947 --> 00:01:45.491
She looked me in the eye and said.

11
00:01:46.034 --> 00:01:47.493
"No. he didn't make it."

12
00:01:50.038 --> 00:01:52.915
I had them put him in a Special room
and clean him up.

13
00:01:53.458 --> 00:01:59.421
And that was the one nice thing.
is I got to be alone with him.

14
00:02:00.757 --> 00:02:07.471
And I got to kiss him on the forehead
and. you know. tell him what I felt.

15
00:02:45.426 --> 00:02:46.677
When I started seeing the news clips

16
00:02:46.761 --> 00:02:49.138
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

17
00:02:49.222 --> 00:02:51.223
the day he died.

18
00:02:51.307 --> 00:02:52.474
my heart sank.

19
00:02:54.644 --> 00:03:00.065
Michael was the most exciting performer

20
00:03:00.150 --> 00:03:02.609
I had ever seen in my life.

21
00:03:04.779 --> 00:03:08.323
He was the ultimate pop Superstar.

22
00:03:09.826 --> 00:03:12.953
He wanted. more than anything.
for his legacy to be

23
00:03:13.079 --> 00:03:16.331
he is the greatest performer of all time.

24
00:03:16.416 --> 00:03:18.000
And that's what he became.

25
00:04:33.451 --> 00:04:35.827
I grew up in East Chicago. Indiana.

26
00:04:38.289 --> 00:04:39.289
Katherine Jackson
MICHAEL'S MOTHER

27
00:04:39.374 --> 00:04:42.209
My mother and father divorced when
I was at a young age. about six years old.

28
00:04:43.878 --> 00:04:45.170
My mother was Baptist.

29
00:04:45.296 --> 00:04:48.173
And my sister and I sang in the Baptist choir.

30
00:04:49.008 --> 00:04:51.510
It made us have a love for music.

31
00:04:54.013 --> 00:04:57.599
My father used to listen
to the country music all the time.

32
00:04:57.684 --> 00:05:03.480
and out of Chicago came a show.
on the radio. called Suppertime Frolic.

33
00:05:06.192 --> 00:05:09.152
And then on Saturdays.
he would listen to the Grand Ole Opty

34
00:05:09.529 --> 00:05:11.029
that came out of NashviIIe.

35
00:05:12.365 --> 00:05:16.368
Some of the people were Ernest Tubb.
that's ancient.

36
00:05:16.494 --> 00:05:19.288
Let me... Let the people know how old I am.

37
00:05:23.543 --> 00:05:26.336
We had a club called the Sub-Debs.

38
00:05:32.176 --> 00:05:36.054
We used to give teenage parties
for all the kids around there.

39
00:05:36.389 --> 00:05:37.556
and that's where I met Joe.

40
00:05:40.018 --> 00:05:42.728
I think I was around 17 years old.

41
00:05:43.146 --> 00:05:48.400
He would always ask me for a dance
when the music was slow.

42
00:05:51.571 --> 00:05:54.156
He seemed very kind. very sweet.

43
00:05:57.410 --> 00:05:58.827
Joseph was in a group.

44
00:05:59.203 --> 00:06:03.707
Besides me leaving singing with my sister.
I started singing with him.

45
00:06:04.334 --> 00:06:07.878
And we would sing and harmonise together a lot.

46
00:06:10.923 --> 00:06:14.092
Then the children came along.
and I kept singing.

47
00:06:17.555 --> 00:06:18.597
Rebbie Jackson
MICHAEL'S SISTER

48
00:06:18.723 --> 00:06:20.640
2300 Jackson St. in that little house.

49
00:06:20.725 --> 00:06:23.435
I was the only one born in that house.

50
00:06:23.686 --> 00:06:25.896
We had two bedrooms in our home.

51
00:06:26.689 --> 00:06:30.108
And I and my Sisters. Janet and La Toya.
Slept in the living room.

52
00:06:30.193 --> 00:06:32.444
Living Room
Gary. Indiana 2010

53
00:06:32.528 --> 00:06:34.571
We had a couch that let out into a bed.

54
00:06:34.655 --> 00:06:36.490
My brothers Slept in one room.

55
00:06:36.574 --> 00:06:38.158
Boy's Bedroom
Gary. Indiana 2010

56
00:06:38.242 --> 00:06:40.118
And that room had triple bunk beds.

57
00:06:40.203 --> 00:06:42.204
And they Slept on the bunk beds.

58
00:06:42.288 --> 00:06:44.539
And then my parents slept in the other room.

59
00:06:44.624 --> 00:06:46.541
Parents' Bedroom
GARY. INDIANA 2010

60
00:06:46.626 --> 00:06:49.419
I don't know how I squeezed
all of us in that little house.

61
00:06:49.504 --> 00:06:50.545
Jackson Family Kitchen Gary. Indiana 1960's

62
00:06:50.671 --> 00:06:54.508
Having all my children when I was young
and having them So close together.

63
00:06:55.802 --> 00:07:02.140
every time I would get pregnant.
I was afraid to tell Joe.

64
00:07:04.018 --> 00:07:09.064
We didn't believe in abortion.
so that's why we got so many children.

65
00:07:11.526 --> 00:07:14.319
The children around our neighbourhood.
especially the boys.

66
00:07:14.695 --> 00:07:16.029
they were kind of bad. some of them.

67
00:07:16.114 --> 00:07:19.116
They would break in people's cars and do things.

68
00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:23.662
And our children were never allowed
to go out at night or play with those kids.

69
00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:25.539
J. Randy Taraborrelli
JACKSON'S FRIEND AND BIOGRAPHER

70
00:07:25.623 --> 00:07:28.667
They weren't really social
with the rest of the neighbourhood.

71
00:07:28.793 --> 00:07:33.171
They clung to each other.
and that's how the Jacksons were raised.

72
00:07:33.339 --> 00:07:36.007
Poor? I mean. that was a way of life.

73
00:07:36.092 --> 00:07:37.551
We had plenty of food to eat.

74
00:07:37.635 --> 00:07:39.845
We were like all the other kids in the area.

75
00:07:39.929 --> 00:07:42.347
Michael never thought
he was poor when he was young.

76
00:07:42.432 --> 00:07:44.599
because he did not know what poor was.

77
00:07:44.684 --> 00:07:45.809
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

78
00:07:45.893 --> 00:07:49.271
He thought
everyone lived the way his family did.

79
00:07:49.730 --> 00:07:52.232
We had a rickety washing machine.

80
00:07:52.316 --> 00:07:53.692
We weren't able to buy a new one.

81
00:07:53.943 --> 00:07:56.236
Whenever it washed. it would creak.
You know. make noises...

82
00:07:57.989 --> 00:07:59.406
Something like that.

83
00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:02.909
And Michael. I guess.
was about 11 or 12 months old.

84
00:08:02.994 --> 00:08:05.662
He was just dancing
to the rhythm of the washing machine.

85
00:08:05.955 --> 00:08:08.457
And I knew then that he had a lot of rhythm.

86
00:08:13.087 --> 00:08:16.214
Michael would always do funny things.
anything for a laugh.

87
00:08:16.299 --> 00:08:17.716
Anything for a laugh.

88
00:08:19.051 --> 00:08:23.305
La Toya was always very persnickety
about the way she kept her room.

89
00:08:23.389 --> 00:08:24.556
And she had this beautiful...

90
00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:27.809
I think it was a white satin bedspread
that she had just gotten.

91
00:08:28.811 --> 00:08:31.104
Michael took some invisible ink

92
00:08:31.230 --> 00:08:34.191
and he spread it all over the bedspread.
squirted it all over.

93
00:08:34.275 --> 00:08:36.902
And then he had her come in
and look at it. She was livid.

94
00:08:39.572 --> 00:08:43.325
Michael used to love telling me stories
about Gary. Indiana.

95
00:08:43.409 --> 00:08:45.911
especially how he would have a candy store.

96
00:08:45.995 --> 00:08:48.747
and he would sell candy to all the neighbours.

97
00:08:49.248 --> 00:08:50.999
and to his brothers.

98
00:08:51.083 --> 00:08:54.169
And he never made any money doing it.

99
00:08:54.253 --> 00:09:00.509
but he showed signs of being
an entrepreneur at a very young age.

100
00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:02.219
As kids. we had a lot of fun.

101
00:09:02.303 --> 00:09:03.428
Tito Jackson
MICHAEL'S BROTHER

102
00:09:03.596 --> 00:09:05.764
You know. just playing around
in the neighbourhood.

103
00:09:05.848 --> 00:09:10.519
Playing practical jokes. throwing balloons
out the car windows at bus stops.

104
00:09:10.770 --> 00:09:14.523
singing and dancing to every song
that came on the radio.

105
00:09:17.443 --> 00:09:20.445
Michael would use
some of the money from his candy store

106
00:09:20.530 --> 00:09:22.447
to go and buy 45s.

107
00:09:22.532 --> 00:09:26.243
because in those days.
that's what kids bought. 45s.

108
00:09:26.327 --> 00:09:29.162
And if you were lucky. you'd buy an LP.

109
00:09:29.330 --> 00:09:33.208
But he started listening strongly to James Brown

110
00:09:33.793 --> 00:09:36.670
from the time he was about five years old.

111
00:09:36.796 --> 00:09:41.716
He had a great taste for real R&B.

112
00:09:41.801 --> 00:09:44.219
gritty R&B. like Wilson Pickett.

113
00:09:45.805 --> 00:09:47.597
the Dells.

114
00:09:47.682 --> 00:09:50.725
great singers like Levi Stubbs.

115
00:09:52.562 --> 00:09:56.022
We sang country songs and we sang folk songs.

116
00:09:56.399 --> 00:09:59.317
And then they started singing the Temptations

117
00:09:59.402 --> 00:10:01.653
when we got a television.

118
00:10:02.154 --> 00:10:05.782
My father had a guitar
that he kept locked in the closet.

119
00:10:05.866 --> 00:10:09.119
One day. he didn't lock the closet
and I started playing that thing.

120
00:10:09.203 --> 00:10:13.456
I learn't every song on the radio
and made my brothers sing with me.

121
00:10:13.541 --> 00:10:16.126
Joseph had warned them.
"Don't play my guitar. now."

122
00:10:16.377 --> 00:10:21.214
And so. Tito took it out and played it.
and a string broke.

123
00:10:21.841 --> 00:10:25.176
There was no way of hiding
that he hadn't had his guitar.

124
00:10:25.303 --> 00:10:26.720
He punished him for it.

125
00:10:26.846 --> 00:10:28.722
Then he said.
"Let me hear you play."

126
00:10:28.848 --> 00:10:31.141
And Tito played for him.

127
00:10:31.225 --> 00:10:34.477
Joe just said nothing else to him.
"You can play it if you want to."

128
00:10:35.187 --> 00:10:38.481
Tito had been watching his father play guitar.

129
00:10:38.566 --> 00:10:41.192
but he would come to my house
and he and I would play.

130
00:10:41.319 --> 00:10:42.485
Reynaud Jones
NEIGHBOUR - GARY. INDIANA

131
00:10:42.695 --> 00:10:45.905
And I would play a little something
on my guitar. and then show him.

132
00:10:46.032 --> 00:10:47.907
and then give my guitar to him.

133
00:10:48.159 --> 00:10:49.576
And then he'd tty to play it.

134
00:10:49.702 --> 00:10:52.245
And so we went back and forth like that.

135
00:10:52.371 --> 00:10:56.207
There was a guy across the street
who had one snare drum.

136
00:10:56.709 --> 00:10:58.335
and his name was Milford Hite.

137
00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:00.253
Milford Hite
NEIGHBOUR - GARY. INDIANA

138
00:11:00.379 --> 00:11:01.755
Reynaud said.
"Milford. come over with your drum

139
00:11:01.881 --> 00:11:04.674
"and let's see if we can. you know.
start a little group together."

140
00:11:04.884 --> 00:11:07.385
We played for a while
and then Jackie Jackson came over.

141
00:11:07.720 --> 00:11:08.720
Okay.

142
00:11:08.888 --> 00:11:12.349
Then after Jackie came in. Jermaine came.

143
00:11:12.725 --> 00:11:14.726
Michael and Marlon were just little kids.

144
00:11:15.061 --> 00:11:17.729
And we used to tell them to be quiet.
"Get out of here."

145
00:11:17.855 --> 00:11:19.022
We used to kick them out the room.

146
00:11:19.106 --> 00:11:21.775
And they used to beg to be in the group.

147
00:11:21.901 --> 00:11:24.319
And we just said.
"Your little brother wants to be in the..."

148
00:11:24.403 --> 00:11:27.906
You know. you just said.
"No. get out of here. This is big boy stuff."

149
00:11:28.741 --> 00:11:33.453
The school was giving a programme
and all the parents were invited.

150
00:11:33.954 --> 00:11:37.415
And Michael was singing solo.
CIimb Every Mountain.

151
00:11:37.541 --> 00:11:41.378
And so Joe's father wanted to go also.
so he could hear him.

152
00:11:42.254 --> 00:11:44.422
And Michael starts singing.

153
00:11:44.799 --> 00:11:47.759
I looked around. Joe's father was crying.

154
00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:51.221
I guess he couldn't imagine

155
00:11:51.305 --> 00:11:54.891
that a 5-year-old kid can keep harmony
and sing that well.

156
00:11:54.975 --> 00:11:56.142
But that's what happened.

157
00:11:56.727 --> 00:12:01.272
We heard him sing and we were so taken by that.

158
00:12:02.066 --> 00:12:04.192
We couldn't believe it so we rushed him home.

159
00:12:04.276 --> 00:12:06.111
immediately took him to the room.

160
00:12:06.237 --> 00:12:08.571
And he was in the group. that fast.

161
00:12:11.701 --> 00:12:16.621
The big thing back then was winning
the Roosevelt High School talent show.

162
00:12:16.956 --> 00:12:18.456
In the '50s and the '60s.

163
00:12:18.541 --> 00:12:24.212
talent shows were the key
to getting a career and a record deal.

164
00:12:24.463 --> 00:12:26.923
And that's what they dreamed of.

165
00:12:28.092 --> 00:12:31.219
Initially. Michael was not our lead singer.

166
00:12:31.303 --> 00:12:36.141
It was Jermaine was our lead singer
when we made it to the talent show.

167
00:12:36.726 --> 00:12:40.228
They came to me and asked me
if I would come over

168
00:12:40.312 --> 00:12:41.396
Robert Hite
NEIGHBOUR - GARY. INDIANA

169
00:12:41.480 --> 00:12:44.315
and give them some pointers
on tightening up the group.

170
00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:49.821
I actually decided that we were going
to present the song My Girl.

171
00:12:49.947 --> 00:12:54.492
because it was a song
that I had become very fond of.

172
00:12:54.994 --> 00:12:58.830
Each person would get a chance
to step forward in the song.

173
00:12:58.956 --> 00:13:00.749
and showcase what they could do.

174
00:13:00.958 --> 00:13:04.669
Milford actually sang My Girl along with them.

175
00:13:04.754 --> 00:13:06.755
Reynaud was singing My Girl.

176
00:13:06.839 --> 00:13:11.342
And all of a sudden We said.
"Michael. sing My Girl."

177
00:13:11.427 --> 00:13:14.846
And he hit it. perfect pitch.

178
00:13:16.348 --> 00:13:17.599
And that was it.

179
00:13:17.683 --> 00:13:19.851
That was our secret weapon. quite honestly.

180
00:13:30.654 --> 00:13:33.031
When Michael came in. the crowd just stood up.

181
00:13:34.867 --> 00:13:38.369
They actually broke a couple of chairs
and seats in the auditorium.

182
00:13:44.877 --> 00:13:47.295
It was such a surprise.

183
00:13:47.379 --> 00:13:50.715
And that's when everybody recognised
the kind of talent that was there.

184
00:13:53.969 --> 00:13:56.513
We wanted to win and we won.

185
00:13:57.056 --> 00:13:58.306
It was a really happy moment.

186
00:13:58.390 --> 00:14:01.810
It was just..."Cause that was the thing to win.
Roosevelt's talent show.

187
00:14:01.894 --> 00:14:04.604
We win a Roosevelt's talent show.
it's like signing a contract with Motown.

188
00:14:10.444 --> 00:14:12.654
After the talent show ended.

189
00:14:12.738 --> 00:14:18.785
Joe decided that Reynaud and Milford
weren't going to be rehearsing with them.

190
00:14:19.745 --> 00:14:21.913
And that's what kind of split everything off.

191
00:14:25.793 --> 00:14:29.003
Joseph was. in many ways. a frustrated musician.

192
00:14:29.088 --> 00:14:31.381
He had a band called the Falcons.

193
00:14:31.465 --> 00:14:37.428
And I think to some extent
he wanted to live vicariously

194
00:14:37.513 --> 00:14:41.349
through the success. the possible success.
of his children as musicians.

195
00:14:42.142 --> 00:14:44.018
But Joseph is a very complicated person.

196
00:14:44.103 --> 00:14:47.272
and it's not easy to paint Joseph
with a wide brushstroke.

197
00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:48.982
Bobby Taylor
ARTIST. GORDY & MOTOWN RECORDS

198
00:14:49.066 --> 00:14:50.733
Joe was a tyrant to them.

199
00:14:50.818 --> 00:14:53.444
He was mean to them. He was evil to them.

200
00:14:54.154 --> 00:14:56.906
Michael was very afraid of Joe.

201
00:14:56.991 --> 00:14:59.367
and a lot of times.
he would stay over at my house.

202
00:14:59.451 --> 00:15:01.619
just to get away from Joe.

203
00:15:01.704 --> 00:15:07.959
because he felt Joe had punished him
too much when he was younger.

204
00:15:09.086 --> 00:15:12.255
He had taken a strap
and spanked him a lot of times.

205
00:15:12.339 --> 00:15:14.841
And he felt it was too harsh.

206
00:15:15.009 --> 00:15:20.972
He was a very strong. and often.
as they would tell it. violent disciplinarian.

207
00:15:25.144 --> 00:15:30.732
Michael. Janet and Randy.
and a little bit of Marlon.

208
00:15:31.859 --> 00:15:36.529
I think they got easy street.
"cause they were the babies.

209
00:15:37.323 --> 00:15:41.534
The ones who really got the spankings
in my family. if I remember correctly.

210
00:15:41.619 --> 00:15:42.994
and I'm pretty sure I do.

211
00:15:43.078 --> 00:15:48.625
was myself. Jermaine and Jackie. the older guys.

212
00:15:49.043 --> 00:15:52.253
I'm sort of like five years older than Michael.

213
00:15:52.338 --> 00:15:57.091
So he was more of one of the little guys
that didn't get it the way the big guys did.

214
00:15:57.509 --> 00:15:58.885
I think in later life.

215
00:16:00.512 --> 00:16:03.264
he began to respect Joe more.

216
00:16:03.349 --> 00:16:08.227
because he saw
that he wanted his kids to be somebody.

217
00:16:09.396 --> 00:16:11.564
My uncle worked in the steel mill.

218
00:16:11.690 --> 00:16:15.360
He never wanted his kids to do what he did.
He wanted them to be better.

219
00:16:16.028 --> 00:16:17.111
Ronald & Keith Jackson
JACKSON'S FIRST COUSINS

220
00:16:17.237 --> 00:16:18.488
I seen the steel mill. and I'm gonna tell you...

221
00:16:18.572 --> 00:16:20.490
- It's like working for Satan...
- Do not work there...

222
00:16:20.574 --> 00:16:23.534
...because it's 2.000 degrees out there.
and it's very dangerous.

223
00:16:24.244 --> 00:16:26.371
So. his vision. I respect.

224
00:16:27.039 --> 00:16:31.876
He wanted them to have a better opportunity.
and to do something they love doing.

225
00:16:35.297 --> 00:16:39.634
I think Joe did the right thing
because none of his kids went to prison.

226
00:16:39.718 --> 00:16:42.929
None of his kids were out
on the street using dope.

227
00:16:44.390 --> 00:16:46.349
I think I was raised right.

228
00:16:46.433 --> 00:16:51.229
I think my father did a brilliant job
to take us from Gary. Indiana.

229
00:16:51.313 --> 00:16:56.234
which is a very poverty-stricken town.

230
00:16:56.318 --> 00:17:00.655
and not too many people get out of there
and make something of themselves.

231
00:17:00.948 --> 00:17:03.449
and he had a dream. and he stuck with it.

232
00:17:03.575 --> 00:17:06.828
And he knew how to get there
and he got us there.

233
00:17:07.454 --> 00:17:11.040
It's okay to have fun sometimes
but you have to prepare yourself.

234
00:17:11.125 --> 00:17:15.420
because your adulthood
is gonna be a lot longer than your childhood.

235
00:17:15.629 --> 00:17:19.090
And if you didn't prepare for it.
you're gonna be on The Late Show.

236
00:17:19.758 --> 00:17:24.679
So I think my father prepared his sons
for the future. to be men.

237
00:17:24.763 --> 00:17:27.765
We were men at a very young age.

238
00:17:27.850 --> 00:17:31.436
I remember asking Michael.
"Why do you call him Joseph?"

239
00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:35.148
And it was really clear.
the way Michael explained it.

240
00:17:35.274 --> 00:17:36.816
that they thought of him as Joseph.

241
00:17:37.276 --> 00:17:40.194
They didn't really think of him as their father.
they thought of him as Joseph.

242
00:17:40.279 --> 00:17:42.864
And I thought that was very sad.

243
00:17:43.157 --> 00:17:44.907
That had to hurt even Joseph.

244
00:17:44.992 --> 00:17:47.243
to know that his children
felt that way about him.

245
00:17:47.327 --> 00:17:50.955
but that was the way he designed it.

246
00:17:51.957 --> 00:17:52.999
Katherine Jackson
MICHAEL'S MOTHER

247
00:17:53.125 --> 00:17:54.709
The world now talks
about how mean and evil he is.

248
00:17:54.793 --> 00:17:55.918
He's not that way.

249
00:17:57.129 --> 00:17:59.589
He's just a firm person.

250
00:18:02.801 --> 00:18:08.347
Michael's very close to my mother.
and she was like a comfort to him. I think.

251
00:18:09.475 --> 00:18:12.143
Michael and I had a very special bond.

252
00:18:12.269 --> 00:18:16.606
Michael used to always tell me
that he was so much like me.

253
00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:19.609
And then I used to tell him. I said.

254
00:18:19.693 --> 00:18:24.572
"I can see myself in you.
but I don't want you to be like me."

255
00:18:24.656 --> 00:18:28.034
because I thought I was too easy-going.

256
00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:29.744
trust people too much.

257
00:18:29.828 --> 00:18:32.121
and that's exactly how Michael is.

258
00:18:33.665 --> 00:18:39.003
There was a mystical connection
that made them almost. at times. one.

259
00:18:39.546 --> 00:18:42.882
Michael and Katherine. two peas in a pod.

260
00:18:46.053 --> 00:18:49.305
He was closer to no one else except for her.

261
00:18:51.141 --> 00:18:54.685
Katherine Jackson
was golden where Michael was concerned.

262
00:18:54.895 --> 00:18:56.687
throughout his entire lifetime.

263
00:18:56.814 --> 00:18:57.814
She always cared.

264
00:18:57.898 --> 00:19:03.069
When he went through stages of acne.
she knew how to handle him.

265
00:19:04.196 --> 00:19:07.448
It was almost as if they were

266
00:19:07.533 --> 00:19:10.201
aligned with each other against the world.

267
00:19:10.536 --> 00:19:13.412
And he could always go to Katherine
for anything.

268
00:19:13.539 --> 00:19:16.082
And she would be there for him. 100%.

269
00:19:28.178 --> 00:19:32.056
They had been working on the music
for a long time.

270
00:19:32.432 --> 00:19:34.934
and they wanted to be signed to a label.

271
00:19:35.936 --> 00:19:38.229
We would go to school in the morning.

272
00:19:38.897 --> 00:19:41.607
Then after school.
we'd get home about 3:0000. 3:300.

273
00:19:42.401 --> 00:19:46.779
And my father'd have all the mics set up
and amps on standby.

274
00:19:47.739 --> 00:19:50.241
And we had enough time to just drop our books.

275
00:19:50.367 --> 00:19:56.289
and we would practise. like. four hours.

276
00:19:56.415 --> 00:19:58.124
until about 7:0000 or 8:0000.

277
00:19:58.250 --> 00:20:00.042
And after that.

278
00:20:00.127 --> 00:20:02.503
we would get ready
to go to Chicago or somewhere.

279
00:20:02.588 --> 00:20:04.755
and go do an engagement.

280
00:20:04.965 --> 00:20:06.674
We would play for 45 minutes.

281
00:20:06.758 --> 00:20:10.469
and take 15 minutes off and do our homework.

282
00:20:11.805 --> 00:20:16.309
By the time we was through with our day.
it was about 2:30 in the morning.

283
00:20:16.894 --> 00:20:21.898
And we'd drive back from Chicago to Gary.
get home about 3:00. 4:00 in the morning.

284
00:20:21.982 --> 00:20:23.858
then go to school the next day.

285
00:20:23.942 --> 00:20:27.153
And that's what life was for us
for many years. a lot of work.

286
00:20:28.614 --> 00:20:30.698
We would perform all night.
tell you the truth. every day.

287
00:20:30.782 --> 00:20:33.201
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

288
00:20:33.285 --> 00:20:35.494
We would be dancing. doing James Brown.

289
00:20:35.621 --> 00:20:39.290
and a lot of people throwing money on stage.
and standing ovations.

290
00:20:39.791 --> 00:20:43.461
And then. soon as we drove home.
we'd get up and go to school.

291
00:20:43.587 --> 00:20:47.757
And we couldn't keep our pants up
"cause we had so much money in them.

292
00:20:47.841 --> 00:20:50.009
I mean. change just broke them.

293
00:20:50.177 --> 00:20:52.511
And there was this man's house.
who used to sell candy.

294
00:20:52.638 --> 00:20:56.974
we used to stop there and just load up.
eat candy for days.

295
00:20:58.143 --> 00:21:01.020
They had a studio at home
and they had these big mirrors and stuff.

296
00:21:01.146 --> 00:21:04.982
And they would say. "Do it again.
do it again. do it again. do it again."

297
00:21:05.108 --> 00:21:08.736
And next thing you know.
seven. eight. nine hours go by.

298
00:21:08.820 --> 00:21:11.614
but they were looking for perfection.

299
00:21:11.990 --> 00:21:13.199
Ronnie Rancifer
KEYBOARDIST."JACKSON 5" 1967-77

300
00:21:13.325 --> 00:21:15.326
They were focused.
that's what I liked about them.

301
00:21:15.452 --> 00:21:18.996
They were serious about doing it.
and it was about perfection.

302
00:21:19.206 --> 00:21:24.543
Johnny Jackson and Ronnie Rancifer
were part of the early Jackson 5.

303
00:21:25.295 --> 00:21:29.215
They were not named members

304
00:21:29.341 --> 00:21:33.010
but they were a part of the group.
and an integral part of the group.

305
00:21:33.136 --> 00:21:36.681
Back then. we didn't have
the greatest instruments in the world.

306
00:21:37.182 --> 00:21:41.727
Other big name groups.
they would have big PAs and all that.

307
00:21:42.145 --> 00:21:44.855
Jacksons didn't have that.
but what they had was soul.

308
00:21:45.691 --> 00:21:47.608
See... And soul goes a long way.

309
00:21:47.693 --> 00:21:50.528
You can have $10 jillion
worth of equipment. baby.

310
00:21:50.654 --> 00:21:54.824
but if you ain't got no soul.
you might as well stay home.

311
00:21:55.701 --> 00:22:00.413
In 1967 the Jackson 5 signed for local
record label. Steeltown Records.

312
00:22:01.039 --> 00:22:02.748
They released two songs on the label;
"Big Boy"

313
00:22:02.874 --> 00:22:04.709
and "We Don't Have To Be Over 21
(To Fall In Love).

314
00:22:04.835 --> 00:22:07.753
Neither appeared on any Billboard Chart.

315
00:22:11.717 --> 00:22:16.554
One day. I was setting up a VIP section
for Bobby Taylor.

316
00:22:17.014 --> 00:22:19.890
all of a sudden. I hear the people clapping
and hollering...

317
00:22:20.058 --> 00:22:22.351
Weldon Arthur McDougal III - A & R
EXECUTIVE. MOTOWN RECORDS 1969-80

318
00:22:22.436 --> 00:22:25.688
And so I come out of the office and I look
and there was the Jackson 5.

319
00:22:25.772 --> 00:22:27.773
Well. they are pretty good.

320
00:22:30.402 --> 00:22:33.696
Joe Jackson said.
"Listen. man. we wanna be on Motown."

321
00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:36.574
And I said.
"Man. I can't get nobody on the label."

322
00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:41.620
And he said. "Well. do you know anybody
you could introduce me to at Motown?"

323
00:22:42.748 --> 00:22:45.708
I was so excited about them.

324
00:22:45.792 --> 00:22:48.377
I told Bobby Taylor that Thursday about them.

325
00:22:48.462 --> 00:22:49.920
He said.
"Okay. I'll look at them."

326
00:22:50.088 --> 00:22:53.299
I met them in 1968. at the Regal Theater.

327
00:22:53.717 --> 00:22:55.634
I was headlining the show.

328
00:22:55.761 --> 00:22:56.761
They were the opening act.

329
00:22:56.887 --> 00:23:00.389
and I was introduced to them by the promoter.

330
00:23:00.474 --> 00:23:04.352
Berry Gordy. President of Motown.
gave him permission

331
00:23:04.436 --> 00:23:09.940
to produce any act that he wanted
and they would listen to it.

332
00:23:10.609 --> 00:23:14.362
He. at that time. had a group
called Bobby Taylor and the Vancouvers.

333
00:23:14.446 --> 00:23:17.656
They had records on the radio
that were going really well and stuff.

334
00:23:25.082 --> 00:23:30.127
I liked the way he sang."cause he was
a star vocalist in his own right.

335
00:23:36.676 --> 00:23:40.805
He knew how to do it. when to do it.
why to do it. and why not to do it.

336
00:23:41.264 --> 00:23:43.849
I saw this little kid spinning and stuff.
I said. "Dang.

337
00:23:44.184 --> 00:23:48.354
"Send him upstairs when they finish.
I want to talk to this kid."

338
00:23:49.314 --> 00:23:52.149
Never thought about recording him at that time.

339
00:23:52.317 --> 00:23:55.152
I said. "This little guy.
I wanna see what's happening."

340
00:23:55.987 --> 00:24:02.660
He was a kid that would worry you. bug you.
until you had to do something with him.

341
00:24:03.662 --> 00:24:07.206
Instead of him going back
to Gary. Indiana. from Chicago

342
00:24:07.332 --> 00:24:12.336
every night. he'd go and ask Joseph
if he could stay with me.

343
00:24:12.838 --> 00:24:15.464
and spend a night at the hotel with me.

344
00:24:15.549 --> 00:24:18.801
So he stayed in my face for 100 straight days.

345
00:24:19.136 --> 00:24:21.512
from the time that we woke up in the morning.

346
00:24:21.638 --> 00:24:24.014
and I'd take and feed this kid.

347
00:24:24.141 --> 00:24:29.061
It was pure. This kid wanted what he got.

348
00:24:29.855 --> 00:24:32.356
He was a workaholic.

349
00:24:32.566 --> 00:24:34.567
Bobby Taylor worked hard.

350
00:24:34.693 --> 00:24:37.528
I mean. I can't say it enough.
I want people to know.

351
00:24:37.904 --> 00:24:41.782
He worked harder on them
than he did with the Vancouvers.

352
00:24:41.867 --> 00:24:44.243
My motivation was Michael.

353
00:24:45.245 --> 00:24:51.208
I just figured this kid here.
he's an adult in kid's clothing.

354
00:24:52.335 --> 00:24:53.711
That was my only motivation.

355
00:24:53.879 --> 00:24:57.882
Everybody around here knew
that Michael Jackson was "it."

356
00:24:59.092 --> 00:25:01.719
The world just didn't know it.

357
00:25:01.887 --> 00:25:03.137
Bobby was pushing.

358
00:25:03.221 --> 00:25:04.722
When I say he was pushing.

359
00:25:04.848 --> 00:25:09.435
the next time I seen Bobby or I seen the group.

360
00:25:09.561 --> 00:25:12.897
he had called me and said
he's working at the Apollo.

361
00:25:13.398 --> 00:25:17.610
And come over to the Apollo.
he got a surprise for me.

362
00:25:17.944 --> 00:25:21.739
And when I went to the Apollo.
the Jackson 5 was on the bill.

363
00:25:21.907 --> 00:25:24.033
Apollo Theater Harlem.
New York City

364
00:25:24.117 --> 00:25:27.661
The Apollo was known
as the greatest R&B showroom in the world.

365
00:25:27.746 --> 00:25:29.955
because many albums had been made from there.

366
00:25:30.081 --> 00:25:32.708
James Brown. Live at the Apollo.

367
00:25:32.792 --> 00:25:35.169
Jackie Wilson played the Apollo.

368
00:25:35.253 --> 00:25:37.713
GIadys Knight and the Pips played the Apollo.

369
00:25:37.797 --> 00:25:39.924
Smokey Robinson and the Miracles.

370
00:25:40.258 --> 00:25:43.511
Everybody who played the Apollo was a star.

371
00:25:43.595 --> 00:25:47.515
And everybody who was underneath them on a bill

372
00:25:47.599 --> 00:25:50.434
was trying to gain that national fame.

373
00:25:50.602 --> 00:25:55.356
And if you make it there.
you're assured of stardom

374
00:25:55.440 --> 00:25:59.818
because people knew
that you've got something very special.

375
00:25:59.945 --> 00:26:01.153
It was a very tough audience.

376
00:26:01.279 --> 00:26:04.907
And if they did not like you.
and you were not a good live act.

377
00:26:05.116 --> 00:26:09.245
even though you may have a hit record.
they'd boo you off the stage.

378
00:26:10.121 --> 00:26:12.706
The Jackson 5 tore that place up.

379
00:26:12.791 --> 00:26:17.294
I mean. I've never seen an act
that nobody never heard of.

380
00:26:17.420 --> 00:26:18.921
didn't have a record.

381
00:26:19.005 --> 00:26:22.258
and. I mean.
the people kept hollering. "Jackson 5!"

382
00:26:22.342 --> 00:26:27.805
On the same show was the 5 Stairsteps.
and they were young kids. too.

383
00:26:27.973 --> 00:26:31.809
or they were about the same age
as the Jackson 5.

384
00:26:32.185 --> 00:26:34.603
And they were complaining.

385
00:26:34.813 --> 00:26:38.023
they wanted to get the Jackson 5 off of the show

386
00:26:38.149 --> 00:26:41.902
because every time they went on.
people just hollered.

387
00:26:41.987 --> 00:26:44.863
"Jackson 5! Jackson 5! Jackson 5!"

388
00:26:45.824 --> 00:26:48.659
And I said.
"Wow! I ain't never seen nothing like this."

389
00:26:52.831 --> 00:26:53.831
Martha Reeves
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

390
00:26:53.957 --> 00:26:57.668
My very first time that I saw Michael Jackson
was at the Apollo Theater in New York.

391
00:27:05.010 --> 00:27:09.221
He and his family were a self-contained act.
which was very unusual.

392
00:27:09.639 --> 00:27:12.975
And yet there was a guitarist in the group
and a bassist in the group.

393
00:27:13.059 --> 00:27:15.144
and keyboard and drums.

394
00:27:22.402 --> 00:27:23.902
They'd won a contest.

395
00:27:24.029 --> 00:27:27.406
They'd won at the Apollo Theater Amateur Night.

396
00:27:27.532 --> 00:27:31.869
and their prize was to open the show
for the great James Brown.

397
00:27:31.995 --> 00:27:34.705
Well. he broke out into this James Brown.
I Got the Feelin'.

398
00:27:34.831 --> 00:27:38.375
and doing his little toes and dancing
and looking like James.

399
00:27:38.501 --> 00:27:40.210
if James were a wind-up toy.

400
00:27:40.503 --> 00:27:42.379
And it was amazing.

401
00:27:42.547 --> 00:27:43.631
Rebbie Jackson
MICHAEL'S SISTER

402
00:27:43.715 --> 00:27:46.425
He would perform and do the moves
and routine that everyone else was doing.

403
00:27:46.551 --> 00:27:50.512
He used to do Fred Astaire and James Cagney.

404
00:27:50.597 --> 00:27:54.266
Then all of a sudden. he would add
a little bit of something in there. different.

405
00:27:54.392 --> 00:27:56.852
And that was him feeling what he was doing.

406
00:27:57.604 --> 00:28:00.648
He excited me. I saw all of this in him.

407
00:28:00.732 --> 00:28:03.067
I saw things that he could do that I couldn't.

408
00:28:04.235 --> 00:28:07.029
He had the makings of a great singer.

409
00:28:07.197 --> 00:28:10.532
Michael had universal appeal
back when he was real young.

410
00:28:10.617 --> 00:28:13.994
I mean. we weren't really into marketing
or anything like that.

411
00:28:14.079 --> 00:28:15.829
but it was already there.

412
00:28:15.914 --> 00:28:18.707
I think the word for it.
the phraseology. would be.

413
00:28:18.792 --> 00:28:23.379
"A diamond in the rough."
without very many edges to buff off.

414
00:28:28.301 --> 00:28:30.135
With the rest of the brothers. now.

415
00:28:30.553 --> 00:28:32.054
Jermaine stuttered.

416
00:28:32.305 --> 00:28:34.807
And he always thought
that if he stuttered when he talked.

417
00:28:34.933 --> 00:28:36.225
that he would do it when he sang.

418
00:28:37.060 --> 00:28:39.937
So I had to push Jermaine more than I had
to push anyone else.

419
00:28:40.105 --> 00:28:44.274
And that's all I used.
Jermaine. Michael and Jackie.

420
00:28:44.609 --> 00:28:47.152
I did not use Marlon. did not use Tito.

421
00:28:47.445 --> 00:28:49.405
They couldn't sing. right?

422
00:28:49.489 --> 00:28:52.116
And I told them. "Learn. Listen and learn."

423
00:28:52.283 --> 00:28:55.285
The complete group was not just those five boys.

424
00:28:55.787 --> 00:28:58.455
The complete group had two other ones with them.

425
00:28:58.665 --> 00:29:00.666
one was Johnny Jackson. the drummer.

426
00:29:00.792 --> 00:29:03.335
one was Ronnie Rancifer. the pianist.

427
00:29:03.920 --> 00:29:06.922
which made the music for the group.

428
00:29:07.006 --> 00:29:09.591
Without them.
there wouldn't have been this Jackson 5.

429
00:29:11.761 --> 00:29:14.805
Every producer
has their own method to the madness.

430
00:29:14.931 --> 00:29:16.974
and Bobby's was pretty cool.

431
00:29:17.100 --> 00:29:19.893
He had the old-school roughness on that.
you know.

432
00:29:19.978 --> 00:29:22.020
You have to have a certain kind of roughness.

433
00:29:22.147 --> 00:29:23.522
a certain kind of discipline.

434
00:29:23.648 --> 00:29:28.444
He felt Michael had something so special.
and he told that to him.

435
00:29:29.654 --> 00:29:30.696
But he said.

436
00:29:30.822 --> 00:29:35.784
"Do not think
just me telling you makes it happen.

437
00:29:36.536 --> 00:29:38.495
"It does not.

438
00:29:38.621 --> 00:29:43.625
"You've gotta work and continue to work
for what you achieve.

439
00:29:43.710 --> 00:29:45.502
"It will never be easy."

440
00:29:45.837 --> 00:29:48.964
He wasn't always patient.

441
00:29:49.048 --> 00:29:52.426
He wasn't always saying things
that you wanna hear.

442
00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:54.178
or saying it right.

443
00:29:54.304 --> 00:29:59.850
But what he said and what he was doing
was just trying to make them stars.

444
00:30:00.477 --> 00:30:04.897
Our last day at the Regal Theater

445
00:30:05.023 --> 00:30:07.274
is when I went to Joe. I said.

446
00:30:07.358 --> 00:30:10.694
"Say now. why don't you let me
put these kids at Motown?"

447
00:30:13.364 --> 00:30:16.867
And Joe said those words to me.
"Man. I thought you'd never ask."

448
00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:23.081
We were in New York City.

449
00:30:23.208 --> 00:30:24.208
Tito Jackson
MICHAEL'S BROTHER

450
00:30:24.334 --> 00:30:27.795
And we had just finished
performing with James Brown.

451
00:30:27.879 --> 00:30:29.546
We were opening up for him.

452
00:30:30.715 --> 00:30:33.550
Bobby Taylor had been begging Berry
to check us out.

453
00:30:34.052 --> 00:30:35.260
Berry Gordy - FOUNDER.
MOTOWN RECORD CORPORATION

454
00:30:35.386 --> 00:30:38.180
And he wouldn't do it
because he had another kid on his label.

455
00:30:38.723 --> 00:30:43.352
And he was catching a lot of flak from the state

456
00:30:43.436 --> 00:30:47.105
about working this kid who's underage.

457
00:30:47.232 --> 00:30:51.819
Berry would say. "I never wanna have
anything to do with kids in this business.

458
00:30:51.903 --> 00:30:52.945
"It's too much problems.

459
00:30:53.071 --> 00:30:56.865
"I can't even handle one.
What am I gonna do with five?"

460
00:30:56.950 --> 00:30:59.201
And the one kid was little Stevie Wonder.

461
00:31:01.412 --> 00:31:03.956
I drove Michael. Marlon.

462
00:31:05.250 --> 00:31:08.210
Tommy Chong. who was in my band.
from Cheech and Chong.

463
00:31:08.294 --> 00:31:10.712
from Chicago to Detroit.

464
00:31:10.797 --> 00:31:13.423
I take Michael directly to Motown.

465
00:31:13.925 --> 00:31:17.261
So I said. "Berry. I've got these kids here

466
00:31:17.387 --> 00:31:20.264
"and they're number one coming
out of the block."

467
00:31:20.515 --> 00:31:22.891
I said. "The lead singer's eight.

468
00:31:23.434 --> 00:31:25.644
"He can out-dance anybody you ever saw.

469
00:31:25.770 --> 00:31:27.312
"Jackie Wilson. James Brown.

470
00:31:27.438 --> 00:31:32.526
"If you close your eyes and listen to him
after I finish teaching him.

471
00:31:32.610 --> 00:31:34.278
"the best singer you ever heard in your life."

472
00:31:34.404 --> 00:31:40.617
It was not easy to get a children's group
signed to Motown.

473
00:31:41.119 --> 00:31:45.414
And Bobby Taylor knew that when he called Berry

474
00:31:45.748 --> 00:31:49.585
and said. "I've got something so special.
you gotta see it."

475
00:31:50.837 --> 00:31:53.297
that Berry would jump once he did.

476
00:31:53.464 --> 00:31:58.135
Because he would not have taken them
to Berry to waste his time.

477
00:31:59.470 --> 00:32:05.809
The next morning. Berry Gordy
called me from Los Angeles. and he says.

478
00:32:05.935 --> 00:32:07.978
"I want you to bring them out here."

479
00:32:10.273 --> 00:32:11.773
That's how they got to Motown.

480
00:32:18.489 --> 00:32:20.282
Going to California.
the happiest day of my life.

481
00:32:20.366 --> 00:32:21.450
Katherine Jackson
MICHAEL'S MOTHER

482
00:32:24.162 --> 00:32:28.165
Joseph had promised me that one day
we would go to California.

483
00:32:29.500 --> 00:32:32.085
I'd tell him. "No."
I said. "Your promise came true.

484
00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:34.963
"but you didn't bring me there.
the children did."

485
00:32:39.177 --> 00:32:41.970
Berry Gordy was having a party for Diana Ross.

486
00:32:42.055 --> 00:32:43.597
It was her birthday.

487
00:32:43.681 --> 00:32:47.351
So he asked us to perform
at this party for Diana.

488
00:32:48.019 --> 00:32:49.728
and of course we did.

489
00:32:49.854 --> 00:32:54.733
And at that party was. like. the Temptations.
Smokey. the Vandellas.

490
00:32:54.859 --> 00:32:58.070
the Supremes. Four Tops.

491
00:32:58.196 --> 00:33:01.281
And here we are performing their songs to them.

492
00:33:01.366 --> 00:33:02.699
So we was quite nervous.

493
00:33:03.576 --> 00:33:04.660
Dionne Warwick
SINGER

494
00:33:04.744 --> 00:33:08.538
I first met Michael. he was.
I think he was 10 years old.

495
00:33:08.665 --> 00:33:10.666
He was flown out with his brothers

496
00:33:10.750 --> 00:33:13.335
to sing for Berry Gordy. Jr.

497
00:33:14.045 --> 00:33:17.547
Berry had invited a bunch of people
up to his home.

498
00:33:17.674 --> 00:33:22.052
This little bitty thing came in
and he sat down next to me

499
00:33:22.887 --> 00:33:25.555
and he looked at me and he says.
"And who are you?"

500
00:33:25.682 --> 00:33:28.392
I said. "I'm Dionne Warwick. Who are you?"

501
00:33:29.060 --> 00:33:30.686
"I'm Michael Jackson."

502
00:33:30.770 --> 00:33:35.190
I said. "Nice to know you. Michael Jackson.
And what do you do. Michael Jackson?"

503
00:33:35.733 --> 00:33:38.026
He says. "Oh. I sing."

504
00:33:38.861 --> 00:33:42.406
I said. "You sing? Can you sing?"

505
00:33:42.865 --> 00:33:45.075
He said. "Yes. I can sing."

506
00:33:45.618 --> 00:33:49.204
I mean. little feisty. beautiful young boy.

507
00:33:49.288 --> 00:33:52.541
I said. "Well. that's what we're here for.
We're gonna see if you can sing."

508
00:34:00.591 --> 00:34:03.510
Watching them perform was excitement.

509
00:34:03.594 --> 00:34:04.636
Brenda Holloway
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

510
00:34:04.762 --> 00:34:06.930
Everyone in the group was an individual.

511
00:34:09.976 --> 00:34:13.103
And I feel that every one of them
could have gone on their own.

512
00:34:13.229 --> 00:34:14.771
But Michael was the star.

513
00:34:21.821 --> 00:34:26.199
They came in and they sang a few songs.

514
00:34:26.284 --> 00:34:28.368
They sang a couple songs
by James Brown. you know.

515
00:34:28.453 --> 00:34:29.494
Smokey Robinson
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

516
00:34:29.620 --> 00:34:35.125
and Michael did the James Brown dances.
and he really did them.

517
00:34:35.251 --> 00:34:39.004
He's 10 years old and he was dancing
like he was about 30.

518
00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:43.800
How in the world could this little boy.
and he was a kid.

519
00:34:43.926 --> 00:34:45.260
be so talented?

520
00:34:45.344 --> 00:34:47.679
That's what everybody went away talking about.

521
00:34:52.685 --> 00:34:56.063
I think all of us Motown artists were astonished

522
00:34:56.147 --> 00:34:57.189
Kim Weston
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

523
00:34:57.315 --> 00:35:01.109
because here's a kid that. you know.
seemed to have no fear.

524
00:35:01.194 --> 00:35:07.324
You know. when the music hit. he was ready.
you know. or ready before the music hit.

525
00:35:07.658 --> 00:35:09.534
He said.
"I want you to know something. too."

526
00:35:09.660 --> 00:35:10.911
I said. "What's that?"

527
00:35:10.995 --> 00:35:14.372
"You sang a song about my name. Michael."

528
00:35:15.500 --> 00:35:18.794
I said. "Yeah.
You think that song was for you?"

529
00:35:20.338 --> 00:35:22.130
He said. "Wasn't it?"

530
00:35:24.467 --> 00:35:28.053
He was an adorable child.
It was a wonderful meeting.

531
00:35:28.805 --> 00:35:31.014
They loved it. They enjoyed it.

532
00:35:31.390 --> 00:35:33.183
That was our audition.

533
00:35:34.393 --> 00:35:37.562
So I'm very proud of that moment in our life.

534
00:35:42.193 --> 00:35:44.152
There was another world about to open

535
00:35:44.237 --> 00:35:45.278
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

536
00:35:45.363 --> 00:35:47.656
and he was ready to delve into it.

537
00:35:47.865 --> 00:35:49.116
Marvin Gaye

538
00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:50.325
Junior Walker

539
00:35:50.409 --> 00:35:52.119
When you went to Motown. it was...
Everyone was there.

540
00:35:52.203 --> 00:35:53.620
The Isley Brothers

541
00:35:53.704 --> 00:35:54.746
Kim Weston

542
00:35:54.872 --> 00:35:55.956
Edwin Starr

543
00:35:56.040 --> 00:35:57.082
Jimmy Ruffin

544
00:35:57.208 --> 00:36:00.710
It was like Disneyland. You saw Smokey.
you saw Mary. you saw Diana Ross.

545
00:36:00.837 --> 00:36:04.714
But everybody was trying
to perfect their artistry.

546
00:36:04.841 --> 00:36:07.175
The feeling at Motown was it was a family.
a musical family.

547
00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:08.510
Valerie Simpson & Nickolas Ashford

548
00:36:08.594 --> 00:36:09.761
SINGERS & SONGWRITERS.
"ASHFORD & SIMPSON"

549
00:36:09.887 --> 00:36:13.557
And we all were a part of excellence
and greatness. musical greatness.

550
00:36:13.683 --> 00:36:16.726
And we so were fans of each other's work.

551
00:36:16.853 --> 00:36:20.063
so that when we saw each other.
it was just instant love.

552
00:36:20.189 --> 00:36:23.942
We got. "We knew what you were doing.
I heard what you're working on."

553
00:36:24.068 --> 00:36:26.695
And it just... We kept pushing each other.

554
00:36:26.904 --> 00:36:29.030
When you start working
with the best in the business

555
00:36:29.115 --> 00:36:30.532
Russell Thompkins. Jr.
LEAD SINGER."THE STYLISTICS"

556
00:36:30.616 --> 00:36:32.325
that are teaching you how to dance.
how to play this

557
00:36:32.410 --> 00:36:35.745
and teaching you how to sing this.
putting you at the piano.

558
00:36:35.872 --> 00:36:40.292
vocal coaches. dancing coaches.
people who teach you how to talk.

559
00:36:40.418 --> 00:36:43.545
When you work with that from the time
that you're a young man.

560
00:36:43.713 --> 00:36:46.464
you grow up with so much influence.

561
00:36:46.632 --> 00:36:49.259
So it wasn't just the fact
that Michael Jackson

562
00:36:49.385 --> 00:36:53.263
was born with so much great talent.
He always had it around him.

563
00:36:58.561 --> 00:37:00.562
Michael Jackson studied all the artists.
all the great artists.

564
00:37:00.646 --> 00:37:01.730
Jimmy Ruffin
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

565
00:37:04.150 --> 00:37:06.818
He studied me. he studied Marvin Gaye.
he studied Stevie Wonder.

566
00:37:06.944 --> 00:37:08.236
He studied everybody.

567
00:37:08.321 --> 00:37:12.991
We were the best in the country at the time.

568
00:37:18.414 --> 00:37:21.499
The first time I saw them perform
was in San Francisco

569
00:37:21.626 --> 00:37:23.418
and I was like. "Wow."

570
00:37:23.502 --> 00:37:25.837
It was like. "There's nobody that good."

571
00:37:31.510 --> 00:37:34.804
Berry Gordy was like.
"Keep your cards close to your chest.

572
00:37:35.264 --> 00:37:37.432
"Don't let people know what you're thinking.

573
00:37:38.142 --> 00:37:41.436
"Don't let the artists know
how much people like them."

574
00:37:41.979 --> 00:37:43.688
He was a shrewd guy.

575
00:37:46.484 --> 00:37:51.446
Berry looked after every aspect
of an artist's career.

576
00:37:51.530 --> 00:37:55.909
Now. some may complain today
that they didn't get paid enough royalties

577
00:37:55.993 --> 00:37:59.788
and they never received
a lot of their publishing.

578
00:37:59.872 --> 00:38:01.456
But I'll tell you something.

579
00:38:01.999 --> 00:38:05.710
Berry Gordy made these artists.

580
00:38:06.170 --> 00:38:07.879
Everybody. I think.
had different relationships with Berry.

581
00:38:08.005 --> 00:38:09.005
Abdul "Duke" Fakir
ARTIST."THE FOUR TOPS"

582
00:38:09.131 --> 00:38:11.967
We had a great relationship with Berry
and we still do.

583
00:38:12.051 --> 00:38:16.179
He gave us... He promised us things
that he made come true.

584
00:38:16.305 --> 00:38:21.142
that he couldn't put in the contract.
But he promised them and kept his word.

585
00:38:21.227 --> 00:38:27.482
What he saw in the Jackson 5
was a children's group that could transcend

586
00:38:27.984 --> 00:38:32.028
every age group.
And he nurtured their talents.

587
00:38:32.697 --> 00:38:34.572
He knew he had something special.

588
00:38:35.032 --> 00:38:38.034
I made him sit in while I was doing the music

589
00:38:38.160 --> 00:38:39.202
Bobby Taylor
ARTIST. GORDY & MOTOWN RECORDS

590
00:38:39.829 --> 00:38:41.579
that they had to work with.

591
00:38:41.914 --> 00:38:46.251
They were with me 200 hours a day.

592
00:38:46.377 --> 00:38:49.254
Being attentive. if I saw somebody sleeping.

593
00:38:49.380 --> 00:38:51.506
then I would send them back to the house

594
00:38:51.590 --> 00:38:53.758
and tell them.
"I don't wanna see you for a week."

595
00:38:53.884 --> 00:38:56.386
They worked hard. they really worked hard.

596
00:38:57.888 --> 00:39:02.851
Michael now would stay
over at Diana Ross's house and rehearse.

597
00:39:03.060 --> 00:39:05.770
He really liked Diana Ross and she liked him.

598
00:39:06.230 --> 00:39:08.565
Diana Ross was showing him off.

599
00:39:08.733 --> 00:39:11.693
She just like...
She was the one that discovered him

600
00:39:11.777 --> 00:39:16.865
and later on I found out that Bobby Taylor
actually discovered him.

601
00:39:18.576 --> 00:39:19.784
I think we were just kids.

602
00:39:19.910 --> 00:39:23.913
We didn't realise all the great accomplishments

603
00:39:24.040 --> 00:39:25.749
that we had achieved.

604
00:39:25.875 --> 00:39:31.171
Seeing Hollywood and playing
with Diana Ross. I mean. we were in heaven.

605
00:39:31.255 --> 00:39:34.924
Just those things alone was priceless to us.

606
00:39:35.092 --> 00:39:37.594
Michael told me when he came to LA.

607
00:39:37.720 --> 00:39:40.597
it was like his whole world had changed.

608
00:39:41.098 --> 00:39:46.436
He could buy as much candy as he wanted
because nobody would say no to him.

609
00:39:53.444 --> 00:39:56.029
Michael and I went to see the Four Tops.

610
00:39:56.113 --> 00:40:01.910
it was around 1971 or '72.

611
00:40:06.082 --> 00:40:08.166
Michael and David just came to the dressing room

612
00:40:08.292 --> 00:40:10.668
and in the dressing room was also Stevie Wonder.

613
00:40:11.462 --> 00:40:15.423
I said to Levi Stubbs.
"You're brilliant. I love your voice."

614
00:40:15.508 --> 00:40:19.427
And Michael looked at him and said.
"I learned everything from you."

615
00:40:19.512 --> 00:40:21.805
And he was cut off. Stevie said. "What?"

616
00:40:22.014 --> 00:40:24.891
And he grabbed Michael
and flung him up against the wall...

617
00:40:24.975 --> 00:40:27.519
And said.
"You learned everything from who?"

618
00:40:27.645 --> 00:40:29.687
And he goes. "You. Stevie. you."

619
00:40:29.814 --> 00:40:32.774
It was so funny. It was so funny.

620
00:40:33.275 --> 00:40:35.151
Levi and I. we never forgot that.

621
00:40:37.113 --> 00:40:40.365
Bobby Taylor and I would take
Michael to the golf course with us.

622
00:40:40.491 --> 00:40:43.743
He had never even picked up
a golf club in his life.

623
00:40:43.828 --> 00:40:46.496
Yet. he was our greatest golf critic.

624
00:40:46.956 --> 00:40:49.416
"Well. Smokey. you know.
you hit your ball over in the woods

625
00:40:49.500 --> 00:40:52.669
"because you didn't have your foot
standing right here..."

626
00:40:53.295 --> 00:40:59.342
"Bobby. see. your club was not. you know..."
He's gonna tell us why we had a bad shot.

627
00:40:59.677 --> 00:41:02.387
But it was fun. He was a great. fun kid.

628
00:41:05.850 --> 00:41:08.518
The first time I heard
I Want You Back in the studio.

629
00:41:08.644 --> 00:41:12.981
I noticed a different kind of brightness
to the movement.

630
00:41:13.065 --> 00:41:14.274
Ronnie Rancifer
KEYBOARDIST."JACKSON 5" 1967-77

631
00:41:14.358 --> 00:41:16.734
other than normal Motown brightness.

632
00:41:17.403 --> 00:41:19.487
It was going in a different direction.

633
00:41:19.572 --> 00:41:23.199
which was good
because Motown's sound was diversified.

634
00:41:23.409 --> 00:41:27.495
When you listened to I Want You Back.
you knew Berry had a knack to get

635
00:41:27.580 --> 00:41:31.541
the best commercial record out of these kids

636
00:41:31.667 --> 00:41:33.918
and make them a worldwide success.

637
00:41:41.677 --> 00:41:47.182
When my sister and my mom first heard
our first hit record. I Want You Back.

638
00:41:47.266 --> 00:41:50.393
my father had sent it over.
they didn't care for it.

639
00:41:50.603 --> 00:41:52.312
I didn't like it at all.

640
00:41:52.396 --> 00:41:54.981
Because the songs that the children sang

641
00:41:55.065 --> 00:41:58.735
was more like the. I should say. soul music.

642
00:41:59.403 --> 00:42:02.363
And to me. I Want You Back
didn't sound that way.

643
00:42:02.948 --> 00:42:06.618
All the songs that was out then
sound so different.

644
00:42:06.744 --> 00:42:09.370
so I guess Berry wanted
to bring out a different style.

645
00:42:09.455 --> 00:42:13.541
Little did they know it was a very big song.
number one.

646
00:42:24.303 --> 00:42:26.429
It was just an unbelievable track.

647
00:42:26.555 --> 00:42:30.141
It just came out of the radio like lightning.

648
00:42:30.267 --> 00:42:34.729
Oh. them Jackson 5. that is a kickin' group.

649
00:42:34.813 --> 00:42:39.275
"Wow. that's them?"
And I had to get used to the song

650
00:42:39.777 --> 00:42:42.445
because even though it was a very big hit.

651
00:42:44.281 --> 00:42:47.492
your brothers singing on a record.
on vinyl. and you hearing it

652
00:42:47.618 --> 00:42:49.118
is something totally different.

653
00:42:49.662 --> 00:42:50.703
We just don't have songs that come and go.

654
00:42:50.788 --> 00:42:53.081
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

655
00:42:53.165 --> 00:42:54.916
we have songs that'll be around all the time.

656
00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:57.710
Like. you'll hear them
on the FM classical stations.

657
00:42:57.795 --> 00:43:00.838
by the Philharmonic Orchestra. things like that.

658
00:43:00.965 --> 00:43:05.176
So it's just not what people call it.
kiddie rock. It's not that.

659
00:43:05.928 --> 00:43:07.971
And a million sellers. a million selling.

660
00:43:08.305 --> 00:43:09.722
J. Randy Taraborrelli
JACKSON'S FRIEND AND BIOGRAPHER

661
00:43:09.807 --> 00:43:13.643
It was difficult to believe
that they were Motown artists.

662
00:43:13.769 --> 00:43:15.645
because they were just kids.

663
00:43:15.771 --> 00:43:19.023
It was as if they had some
kind of stardust rub off on them

664
00:43:19.149 --> 00:43:22.777
because. you know. they were
becoming close to Berry Gordy.

665
00:43:22.861 --> 00:43:25.613
Diana Ross. and to all of my idols.

666
00:43:31.287 --> 00:43:34.247
When I wrote Who's Lovin' You.
I was. you know. in my early 20s.

667
00:43:34.331 --> 00:43:35.373
Smokey Robinson
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

668
00:43:44.800 --> 00:43:49.304
But at least. at that point.
I had had a chance to experience

669
00:43:49.388 --> 00:43:51.347
some life and some love.

670
00:43:51.473 --> 00:43:54.309
I was married. I got married when I was 19.

671
00:43:55.227 --> 00:43:58.980
The subject matter of the song is like a person

672
00:43:59.064 --> 00:44:03.026
who has somebody who really loves them.

673
00:44:03.527 --> 00:44:05.737
And yet they don't appreciate it.
They do the person wrong.

674
00:44:06.030 --> 00:44:08.197
The first time I heard Smokey's
Who's Lovin' You.

675
00:44:08.324 --> 00:44:10.908
my assistant was playing it
and it's one of those.

676
00:44:11.035 --> 00:44:18.041
oh. party. red-light. basement-type.
you know. up on it.

677
00:44:20.377 --> 00:44:22.253
But when Michael got ahold to it.

678
00:44:22.379 --> 00:44:25.715
and Bobby Taylor infused him up with that funk.

679
00:44:25.841 --> 00:44:30.219
man. Michael put that soul
in that song so deep. it was soulful.

680
00:44:48.072 --> 00:44:51.741
How could he possibly know what that song meant?

681
00:44:51.909 --> 00:44:53.576
He sang it like he had written it.

682
00:44:56.246 --> 00:44:59.916
I sing Who's Lovin' You. or part of it.
in my live concerts

683
00:45:00.584 --> 00:45:03.961
and many times. young people have
come up to me after the concert and said.

684
00:45:04.088 --> 00:45:06.422
"Oh. I didn't know
you sang Michael Jackson's song."

685
00:45:13.889 --> 00:45:18.810
A kid. 11 years old. singing that song
with that much emotion? It was incredible.

686
00:45:19.061 --> 00:45:20.103
Unbelievable.

687
00:45:34.618 --> 00:45:36.994
He seemed as if he was an old soul.

688
00:45:37.454 --> 00:45:40.832
that he could take a song like Who's Lovin' You

689
00:45:40.958 --> 00:45:44.794
and he could actually interpret those lyrics

690
00:45:44.920 --> 00:45:46.838
in a way that made you believe

691
00:45:46.964 --> 00:45:50.591
that he had those experiences.
when actually he was 10 years old.

692
00:45:50.968 --> 00:45:54.429
If you didn't know he was a kid.
you'd have thought he was an old man.

693
00:45:55.848 --> 00:45:57.724
But he was singing it from his heart.

694
00:45:57.808 --> 00:46:00.101
You know. Michael's life
was kind of paradoxical to me.

695
00:46:00.185 --> 00:46:03.813
because when he was a child. he was a man.

696
00:46:04.314 --> 00:46:07.108
So when he was a man. he got the chance
to be a child and he took it.

697
00:46:18.996 --> 00:46:24.625
He had a way of interpreting a lyric.
even as a very young boy.

698
00:46:24.835 --> 00:46:27.336
that made you believe the song.

699
00:46:40.893 --> 00:46:42.852
He knew how to perform.

700
00:46:43.228 --> 00:46:46.189
This was. I think. something
that Berry Gordy really liked about Michael

701
00:46:46.315 --> 00:46:48.941
because. not only was he a great vocal talent.

702
00:46:49.026 --> 00:46:50.443
but he was a great performer.

703
00:46:50.527 --> 00:46:52.820
Watching him. as a kid.
be so comfortable performing

704
00:46:52.905 --> 00:46:53.988
Peabo Bryson
SINGER

705
00:46:54.072 --> 00:46:59.202
probably helped me
become a better performer. actually.

706
00:46:59.536 --> 00:47:01.454
His voice was nearly as high as Stevie Wonder's.

707
00:47:01.538 --> 00:47:02.622
Martha Reeves
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

708
00:47:02.706 --> 00:47:04.707
I met Stevie when he was eight years old

709
00:47:04.875 --> 00:47:11.297
and I said. "Here's another little youngster
who's far beyond his age. talent-wise.

710
00:47:11.381 --> 00:47:15.718
"but able to sing adult songs
in perfect-pitched voices.

711
00:47:15.844 --> 00:47:18.179
"real high voices that hadn't changed yet."

712
00:47:26.939 --> 00:47:29.190
His voice and his expressions and his...

713
00:47:29.274 --> 00:47:30.316
Weldon Arthur McDougal III

714
00:47:30.400 --> 00:47:31.442
A & R EXECUTIVE.
MOTOWN RECORDS 1969-80

715
00:47:31.568 --> 00:47:35.196
...charisma start taking these songs over.

716
00:47:36.073 --> 00:47:39.992
Like. if Smokey felt like he did his song

717
00:47:40.077 --> 00:47:42.745
and more people like the way Michael
did it than him.

718
00:47:42.871 --> 00:47:45.706
that's because he did that with all
of his songs at that time.

719
00:47:51.421 --> 00:47:57.134
No matter who it was. the O'Jays. the Dells.
the Whispers or the Beatles.

720
00:47:57.594 --> 00:47:59.387
we wanted to be the best.

721
00:47:59.471 --> 00:48:02.849
And that's what we were striving for.

722
00:48:04.893 --> 00:48:11.566
Berry Gordy did not like the stuff
that Bobby Taylor was recording on them.

723
00:48:11.692 --> 00:48:17.947
I wanted to do the boys a certain way.
but he wanted me to do them his way.

724
00:48:19.283 --> 00:48:23.035
And I says. "I can't do them the way
you want me to do them.

725
00:48:23.120 --> 00:48:24.871
"I must have my own head."

726
00:48:24.955 --> 00:48:26.747
So he says.
"Okay. We're going back to Detroit."

727
00:48:27.082 --> 00:48:28.624
Then he took over.

728
00:48:28.709 --> 00:48:33.796
Berry Gordy. in turn. put his crew together.

729
00:48:34.256 --> 00:48:38.718
The Corporation was established
to bring fresh new material

730
00:48:39.136 --> 00:48:40.803
to the Jackson 5.

731
00:48:40.888 --> 00:48:42.471
Youthful material.

732
00:48:42.764 --> 00:48:48.436
I think he probably felt that Bobby Taylor would

733
00:48:49.771 --> 00:48:54.817
give them more adult material
and forget that they were children.

734
00:48:54.902 --> 00:48:58.654
He saw gazillions. right?

735
00:48:59.072 --> 00:49:00.239
Then he took over.

736
00:49:00.324 --> 00:49:04.994
Bobby Taylor did never get the recognition
he should have gotten

737
00:49:05.621 --> 00:49:07.496
for working with them.

738
00:49:08.790 --> 00:49:11.000
from the group or the public.

739
00:49:13.295 --> 00:49:18.507
Bobby Taylor produced 10 songs on the
album: "Diana Ross Presents The Jackson 5"

740
00:49:20.344 --> 00:49:25.765
During 1969-70 the Jackson 5
released 4 number one singles in a row.

741
00:49:32.648 --> 00:49:34.357
The Corporation. is what they called themselves.

742
00:49:34.441 --> 00:49:39.111
they topped themselves
with those early songs by the Jackson 5.

743
00:49:39.196 --> 00:49:40.696
they were absolutely incredible.

744
00:49:40.822 --> 00:49:42.782
Absolutely incredible.

745
00:49:43.033 --> 00:49:46.869
When my boys had five gold records in a row.

746
00:49:48.997 --> 00:49:53.209
I was very proud of them because I know
it was something that they wanted

747
00:49:53.377 --> 00:49:56.128
and it was their dream.

748
00:49:56.213 --> 00:49:59.382
And they were happy and I was happy.

749
00:49:59.508 --> 00:50:01.550
The whole family was happy about that.

750
00:50:06.348 --> 00:50:08.641
We did a show once for Jesse Jackson.

751
00:50:08.725 --> 00:50:09.809
Dennis Edwards
LEAD SINGER."THE TEMPTATIONS"

752
00:50:09.893 --> 00:50:11.644
You know. Jesse Jackson. he's the activist.

753
00:50:11.728 --> 00:50:15.398
He's got an organisation called PUSH Expo.

754
00:50:15.524 --> 00:50:17.650
He booked the Temptations and the Jackson 5.

755
00:50:17.734 --> 00:50:19.151
They were just up and coming.

756
00:50:19.236 --> 00:50:24.740
We were superstars at that time
and. oh. man. it was so many people.

757
00:50:27.160 --> 00:50:29.495
When they did that show.

758
00:50:30.080 --> 00:50:32.581
the Temptations got a great response.

759
00:50:34.751 --> 00:50:38.504
When the Jackson 5 came on. it was phenomenal.

760
00:50:38.922 --> 00:50:41.215
I mean. almost blew the roof off the place.

761
00:50:45.262 --> 00:50:46.929
They couldn't get us to our limos.

762
00:50:47.014 --> 00:50:50.516
They had to back up an armoured car.
a Brink's car.

763
00:50:50.600 --> 00:50:53.602
It's like a moment in history.

764
00:50:54.438 --> 00:50:59.233
That's when they finally made it
with the black R&B public.

765
00:50:59.693 --> 00:51:02.445
They were just ripe for stardom.

766
00:51:05.282 --> 00:51:08.284
On the stage. he was a different guy.

767
00:51:11.121 --> 00:51:15.583
He was really as much of an actor
in so many ways as he was a singer.

768
00:51:16.209 --> 00:51:17.626
A lot of people always come up
to a lot of us and say

769
00:51:17.753 --> 00:51:20.046
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

770
00:51:20.130 --> 00:51:21.130
it's like two different people.

771
00:51:21.256 --> 00:51:23.215
On stage and off stage.

772
00:51:23.300 --> 00:51:27.970
When we was talking. he's shy
and. you know. very soft spoken.

773
00:51:28.472 --> 00:51:30.973
But just when he jumped
on that stage. he's like...

774
00:51:41.485 --> 00:51:44.111
Well. I mean. he was a different person

775
00:51:44.321 --> 00:51:47.948
and I've never seen
that in another artist's life.

776
00:51:48.575 --> 00:51:50.284
He was like two guys.

777
00:51:50.410 --> 00:51:54.246
Anything he felt that he wanted to do.
he would do it on stage.

778
00:52:07.427 --> 00:52:09.845
The moment he came off of the stage.

779
00:52:09.930 --> 00:52:14.683
he was back to the little boy he was
before he went on stage.

780
00:52:22.025 --> 00:52:24.693
When I get on stage. I really.
totally do. That's with a lot of performers.

781
00:52:24.820 --> 00:52:27.113
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

782
00:52:27.197 --> 00:52:28.197
I've learned that about comedians. too.

783
00:52:28.323 --> 00:52:30.783
It's like when I worked with Richard Pryor
in The Wiz.

784
00:52:30.867 --> 00:52:33.869
A lot of people think he's the funniest guy
to be around 24 hours.

785
00:52:33.954 --> 00:52:36.705
That's not true. He's really shy and quiet.

786
00:52:37.040 --> 00:52:38.791
We were all like that. too.

787
00:52:38.875 --> 00:52:43.045
Singing or dancing
in front of. like. one person. can't do it.

788
00:52:43.130 --> 00:52:46.882
But. like. it's 300.000000. you feel so free.
so much easier.

789
00:52:46.967 --> 00:52:48.050
It's hard to explain.

790
00:52:56.226 --> 00:52:59.311
What motivates Michael Jackson?

791
00:53:00.188 --> 00:53:02.064
That was an audience.

792
00:53:02.482 --> 00:53:03.649
Think about it.

793
00:53:03.733 --> 00:53:09.196
He's shy. he won't look at you. right?

794
00:53:09.364 --> 00:53:10.531
On stage. what is he?

795
00:53:17.080 --> 00:53:18.706
He owns it.

796
00:53:19.249 --> 00:53:21.667
So if I had people looking at him.

797
00:53:21.751 --> 00:53:24.920
I used to bring five. six girls
every time. right?

798
00:53:25.046 --> 00:53:28.340
And I'd say. "Michael. look at that girl. man.
They think you're cute."

799
00:53:28.425 --> 00:53:31.844
Michael would say.
"Dang. Bobby. they said that?"

800
00:53:31.928 --> 00:53:35.222
I said. "You better go out there
and sing now. son."

801
00:53:44.441 --> 00:53:47.526
I said. "You go out there
and you mess up now." I said.

802
00:53:47.611 --> 00:53:49.612
"They're gonna tell all the rest of the girls
out there.

803
00:53:49.696 --> 00:53:52.364
"You're gonna be one ugly little boy
everywhere you go."

804
00:54:01.208 --> 00:54:04.376
He used to go out and do one take.

805
00:54:09.549 --> 00:54:14.428
When we were on the road.
Michael would worry you to death.

806
00:54:14.721 --> 00:54:16.388
I hear somebody knocking on my door and say.

807
00:54:16.473 --> 00:54:21.143
"Hey. man. what's wrong?" "Oh. man.
what you doing? I wanna come in."

808
00:54:21.269 --> 00:54:25.898
So I'd let him in. I'd say. "Man. why don't
you hang out with Jackie and them guys?"

809
00:54:25.982 --> 00:54:28.442
"Hey. man. they got somebody in their room."

810
00:54:30.570 --> 00:54:32.404
I said. "Well. how do you know?"

811
00:54:32.489 --> 00:54:35.241
He said. "'Cause I was listening
to the door for about an hour."

812
00:54:38.662 --> 00:54:41.121
He was like a little boy. I mean. he...

813
00:54:41.248 --> 00:54:42.414
I said. "What were they doing?"

814
00:54:42.499 --> 00:54:44.833
He said. "They were talking.
but they won't let me in."

815
00:54:45.418 --> 00:54:51.173
They were like little kids
and they were very. very happy

816
00:54:51.258 --> 00:54:52.800
and very carefree.

817
00:54:52.926 --> 00:54:55.511
Michael loved being Michael Jackson at that age.

818
00:54:56.596 --> 00:54:59.682
He loved touring. he loved recording at Motown.

819
00:54:59.808 --> 00:55:03.519
He loved his fans. he loved performing.

820
00:55:03.853 --> 00:55:08.774
They had dirt bikes
and they used to go on Saturday mornings.

821
00:55:08.858 --> 00:55:12.027
They'd go to a place where they could ride them.

822
00:55:12.195 --> 00:55:14.613
and Michael used to tear that thing up.

823
00:55:14.698 --> 00:55:17.866
Man. he was flying up and down over the hills.

824
00:55:18.660 --> 00:55:22.288
I thought it was. you know. he was like
any other little boy.

825
00:55:22.664 --> 00:55:25.708
But he was a little boy with a dirt bike.

826
00:55:26.042 --> 00:55:28.460
I mean. they had two or three of them.

827
00:55:28.545 --> 00:55:32.172
So. when people say
that he didn't have a childhood.

828
00:55:32.632 --> 00:55:35.384
far as I'd seen he had a childhood.

829
00:55:35.510 --> 00:55:39.138
When he was a kid. things were a lot simpler.

830
00:55:39.347 --> 00:55:44.560
And I think that. as they got older.
the family became more divided

831
00:55:44.978 --> 00:55:46.979
and other stuff happened
in Michael Jackson's life

832
00:55:47.063 --> 00:55:49.732
to make him wish that he was 12 years old again.

833
00:55:49.858 --> 00:55:53.736
So. when he says he missed out on his childhood.

834
00:55:53.862 --> 00:55:57.531
I've always felt that what he really meant was
that he just missed it very much.

835
00:56:04.748 --> 00:56:06.665
The first time I met him was when he was 14.

836
00:56:06.750 --> 00:56:07.833
Don Black
SONGWRITER."BEN"

837
00:56:07.917 --> 00:56:10.336
full of life. full of ambition.

838
00:56:11.504 --> 00:56:15.090
It was at the peak of his powers.

839
00:56:17.344 --> 00:56:21.388
Fire in his belly and just everything
about him was fabulous.

840
00:56:29.189 --> 00:56:31.523
I wrote it about friendship.

841
00:56:31.608 --> 00:56:34.777
The story is about this boy
who's very seriously ill

842
00:56:34.903 --> 00:56:37.196
and nothing's going right for him.

843
00:56:37.280 --> 00:56:41.283
But a little rat comes along one day.
he sees it in his bedroom.

844
00:56:42.327 --> 00:56:46.955
But it was a lovely little mouse kind of rat.

845
00:56:47.624 --> 00:56:48.999
And he befriends him.

846
00:56:49.918 --> 00:56:54.046
And it makes the boy so much better.
it lifts his spirits up.

847
00:56:54.130 --> 00:56:57.341
And that's how I wrote the song.
about friendship.

848
00:56:57.467 --> 00:56:58.717
It can be about a rat.

849
00:56:58.802 --> 00:57:02.346
"The two of us need look no more.
You're always running here and there."

850
00:57:02.472 --> 00:57:04.473
But it could be about a best friend.

851
00:57:09.854 --> 00:57:14.608
When Michael recorded Ben.
I remember going to the studio

852
00:57:14.692 --> 00:57:17.236
and it was just magical. I just loved it.

853
00:57:17.320 --> 00:57:21.657
I always remember Michael
getting very emotional about that song.

854
00:57:22.200 --> 00:57:25.160
His eyes welled up a bit.

855
00:57:25.286 --> 00:57:26.578
particularly at the middle bit.

856
00:57:26.663 --> 00:57:28.997
I'll never forget that image.

857
00:57:29.124 --> 00:57:32.543
The middle bit was.
"I used to say 'I' and 'me'."

858
00:57:32.669 --> 00:57:35.295
"now it's 'us'. now it's 'we'."

859
00:57:41.511 --> 00:57:43.887
Michael just loved those lines.

860
00:57:44.013 --> 00:57:47.307
In fact. that's why. I think.
we repeat them in the song.

861
00:57:47.392 --> 00:57:48.851
We do it again.

862
00:57:54.190 --> 00:57:56.984
There was a longing. I think.
for love and acceptance.

863
00:57:57.068 --> 00:57:59.403
going all the way back
to when he was a little kid.

864
00:57:59.529 --> 00:58:04.408
And you were able to hear that longing
in his voice.

865
00:58:04.534 --> 00:58:05.617
Singing is passion.

866
00:58:05.702 --> 00:58:06.743
Bobby Taylor
ARTIST. GORDY & MOTOWN RECORDS

867
00:58:06.870 --> 00:58:08.036
You have to do it from inside of you.

868
00:58:08.872 --> 00:58:12.499
It has to come from your soul. your heart.

869
00:58:15.503 --> 00:58:16.920
And Michael Jackson had that.

870
00:58:17.046 --> 00:58:19.673
It wasn't done for the posture of "I did this."

871
00:58:19.757 --> 00:58:21.341
Dionne Warwick
SINGER

872
00:58:21.426 --> 00:58:25.053
It was done because his heart said.
"This is what I need to do." and he did it.

873
00:58:25.430 --> 00:58:26.722
Michael sings like an angel.

874
00:58:26.806 --> 00:58:28.390
He has the voice of an angel and he does...

875
00:58:28.516 --> 00:58:29.558
Kenny Gamble & Leon Huff

876
00:58:29.642 --> 00:58:30.893
PRODUCERS & SONGWRITERS.
PHILADELPHIA INT. RECORDS

877
00:58:31.019 --> 00:58:33.645
Every note is right on it and he was doing
that at nine years old.

878
00:58:33.730 --> 00:58:36.231
I recorded Ben I don't know how long ago.

879
00:58:36.357 --> 00:58:38.650
I mean. I hear it all the time still.
you know. go on and on and on.

880
00:58:38.735 --> 00:58:41.069
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

881
00:58:41.154 --> 00:58:42.571
Yeah. it's selling more now.

882
00:58:42.655 --> 00:58:44.531
So. it's what you leave behind. I think.

883
00:58:51.414 --> 00:58:55.542
There are people who come along
once in a lifetime.

884
00:58:56.085 --> 00:58:58.378
Michael Jackson. he only happens once.

885
00:59:18.024 --> 00:59:21.360
When you think about Michael Jackson.
you think about him as a kid.

886
00:59:21.444 --> 00:59:22.528
Freda Payne
SINGER

887
00:59:22.612 --> 00:59:26.532
Like when he did some
of those earlier songs. like Ben.

888
00:59:33.456 --> 00:59:36.959
And then as he grew and evolved
and became a young man.

889
00:59:38.586 --> 00:59:42.047
I saw the metamorphosis
of a beautiful. beautiful flower.

890
00:59:42.131 --> 00:59:44.424
just blooming and unfolding.

891
00:59:49.889 --> 00:59:51.890
Michael enjoyed what he was doing.

892
00:59:51.975 --> 00:59:53.058
Mickey & Jan Rooney
JACKSON'S FRIENDS

893
00:59:53.142 --> 00:59:58.146
That's why. transition from very young
to getting older.

894
00:59:58.481 --> 01:00:04.987
it's just one year after another.
but doing what the good Lord let us do.

895
01:00:05.488 --> 01:00:08.323
When Michael became a teenager.
his voice changed.

896
01:00:08.408 --> 01:00:11.159
He realised that he would be singing
different types of music.

897
01:00:11.244 --> 01:00:12.244
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

898
01:00:12.328 --> 01:00:15.998
not kiddie pop songs
like he had been most of his career.

899
01:00:17.417 --> 01:00:21.003
The first time we worked
with the Jackson 5 was very exciting.

900
01:00:21.129 --> 01:00:23.338
Because the one thing I noticed about the group.

901
01:00:23.423 --> 01:00:24.423
Brian & Eddie Holland

902
01:00:24.507 --> 01:00:25.591
SONGWRITERS.
HOLLAND-DOZIER-HOLLAND

903
01:00:25.675 --> 01:00:28.927
that they were extremely down to earth.
very mannerable.

904
01:00:29.012 --> 01:00:30.679
very. very polite.

905
01:00:30.805 --> 01:00:34.433
Michael recorded several songs
of mine and the Hollands'

906
01:00:34.517 --> 01:00:35.684
Lamont Dozier
SONGWRITER. HOLLAND-DOZIER-HOLLAND

907
01:00:35.810 --> 01:00:38.145
and Forever Came Today was one of my favourites.

908
01:00:42.859 --> 01:00:46.320
He had such pipes and drama in his voice

909
01:00:46.446 --> 01:00:48.155
to be so young.

910
01:00:52.660 --> 01:00:54.953
He was just one of a kind in that respect.

911
01:00:55.038 --> 01:00:57.164
He really did the songs justice.

912
01:00:58.958 --> 01:01:02.878
I think Michael knew how important lyric
was to the song.

913
01:01:02.962 --> 01:01:04.046
Valerie Simpson & Nickolas Ashford

914
01:01:04.130 --> 01:01:05.547
SINGERS & SONGWRITERS.
"ASHFORD & SIMPSON"

915
01:01:05.673 --> 01:01:08.967
And it had to reach. touch something.
I think. for him to really wanna sing it.

916
01:01:09.052 --> 01:01:12.804
And. you know.
he'd dance and sing at the same time

917
01:01:12.889 --> 01:01:15.724
so it had to correspond with his body. too.

918
01:01:15.808 --> 01:01:19.061
So it all had to be one piece for him.

919
01:01:23.566 --> 01:01:26.902
He didn't want fluff.
He wanted something with legs on it.

920
01:01:27.028 --> 01:01:29.321
something that was gonna last through time

921
01:01:29.405 --> 01:01:31.823
and that's actually what he ended up creating.

922
01:01:32.033 --> 01:01:36.078
The bigger he became as an artist.

923
01:01:36.913 --> 01:01:41.416
the more enamoured he seemed
to be over songwriters.

924
01:01:46.089 --> 01:01:50.592
A lot of people have done those songs
and couldn't get a handle on them

925
01:01:50.718 --> 01:01:53.345
like the Levi Stubbs or Diana Ross.

926
01:01:53.429 --> 01:01:57.224
but he just had a knack. a gift.

927
01:01:57.600 --> 01:02:00.936
He already had a cake
but then he put icing all on top of it.

928
01:02:05.233 --> 01:02:06.775
Around 1974.

929
01:02:07.235 --> 01:02:09.778
they started doing product at Motown
that perhaps wasn't the best.

930
01:02:09.862 --> 01:02:11.196
J. Randy Taraborrelli
JACKSON FRIEND AND BIOGRAPHER

931
01:02:11.280 --> 01:02:14.866
As a fan. I loved songs
like The Boogie Man is gonna get you.

932
01:02:14.951 --> 01:02:18.787
and Lookin' through the Windows. and Skywriter.

933
01:02:18.955 --> 01:02:20.956
but these songs weren't hits.

934
01:02:22.792 --> 01:02:24.292
Joe mentioned to me

935
01:02:24.377 --> 01:02:30.298
several times that he felt like
Motown was taking the group over.

936
01:02:30.425 --> 01:02:33.301
taking them away from his direction.

937
01:02:34.804 --> 01:02:36.555
What happened was that

938
01:02:36.639 --> 01:02:39.099
Marvin Gaye and Stevie Wonder
and Smokey Robinson

939
01:02:39.225 --> 01:02:41.893
were writing and producing
and doing a lot of things at Motown

940
01:02:42.145 --> 01:02:44.479
that the Jacksons had begun
to want to do for themselves.

941
01:02:44.897 --> 01:02:47.733
And to see how Motown treated other artists

942
01:02:47.817 --> 01:02:50.152
and how the other artists was making it.

943
01:02:50.486 --> 01:02:52.070
it was kind of disillusion.

944
01:02:53.990 --> 01:02:57.826
The company was being
run at that time by Ewart Abner.

945
01:02:57.910 --> 01:03:00.787
Berry Gordy was making movies with Diana Ross.

946
01:03:01.164 --> 01:03:03.081
And Abner felt pretty strongly

947
01:03:03.166 --> 01:03:06.334
that they should not be writing
and producing their own music.

948
01:03:06.502 --> 01:03:09.004
that they should just
accept the material that came their way

949
01:03:09.130 --> 01:03:11.089
and just do a good job with it in the studio.

950
01:03:12.759 --> 01:03:14.509
Michael was very disillusioned.

951
01:03:15.136 --> 01:03:17.637
He wanted to not only write his own material

952
01:03:17.805 --> 01:03:19.598
but produce it as well.

953
01:03:19.682 --> 01:03:20.766
He realised

954
01:03:20.850 --> 01:03:24.519
if he was to reach these goals.
he would have to go somewhere else.

955
01:03:26.272 --> 01:03:28.982
Joe Jackson called me and told me

956
01:03:29.108 --> 01:03:30.692
that they were looking for a place to go.

957
01:03:30.818 --> 01:03:31.860
Kenny Gamble & Leon Huff

958
01:03:31.944 --> 01:03:33.195
PRODUCERS & SONGWRITERS.
PHILADELPHIA INT. RECORDS

959
01:03:33.321 --> 01:03:34.529
And of course. Huff and myself.

960
01:03:34.614 --> 01:03:37.491
we tried to get them
for Philly International Records.

961
01:03:37.700 --> 01:03:39.701
But at the same time. CBS

962
01:03:39.994 --> 01:03:42.662
was negotiating with them also.

963
01:03:42.872 --> 01:03:44.956
I wanted to know if there was a shot. a chance.

964
01:03:45.041 --> 01:03:46.541
Ron Alexenburg
SNR. VICE PRESIDENT CBS & EPIC RECORDS

965
01:03:46.626 --> 01:03:50.045
of being able to get involved.
And I was told there was.

966
01:03:51.297 --> 01:03:54.549
The next is. we sat down
and we started to negotiate.

967
01:03:55.301 --> 01:03:57.385
They wanted a million dollars.

968
01:03:57.470 --> 01:03:59.971
And I figured.
"Okay. that's all I could approve up to."

969
01:04:00.056 --> 01:04:01.473
That was my approval level.

970
01:04:02.058 --> 01:04:03.558
I had to go through the ranks

971
01:04:03.684 --> 01:04:07.312
and ll said.
"We have a chance of signing the Jackson 5"

972
01:04:07.396 --> 01:04:09.397
and they said. "They're done."

973
01:04:09.524 --> 01:04:10.816
I said. "No. I'm sorry.

974
01:04:11.025 --> 01:04:13.652
"I believe in them.
I believe that there's a big future.

975
01:04:13.736 --> 01:04:15.237
"I believe that Michael Jackson

976
01:04:15.905 --> 01:04:18.824
"could be one of the biggest stars ever."

977
01:04:20.576 --> 01:04:21.701
That took care of that.

978
01:04:21.869 --> 01:04:25.580
I was handed the letter and they said.
"There's your deal memo. go sign them."

979
01:04:25.998 --> 01:04:27.332
In order to move on and progress.

980
01:04:27.416 --> 01:04:28.500
Katherine Jackson MICHAEL'S MOTHER

981
01:04:28.584 --> 01:04:30.168
Joseph said he had to do it

982
01:04:30.253 --> 01:04:34.256
because he wanted the children
to get credit for their writings and all of that.

983
01:04:34.340 --> 01:04:36.174
and they couldn't do that at Motown.

984
01:04:36.259 --> 01:04:39.761
CBS offered them movies.
they offered them a TV show.

985
01:04:39.887 --> 01:04:41.388
cartoons and everything.

986
01:04:41.848 --> 01:04:45.559
And of course Gamble and Huff. you know.
we couldn't offer them all those things.

987
01:04:46.352 --> 01:04:49.354
So they decided to go with CBS.

988
01:04:49.605 --> 01:04:52.023
Probably the most important signing
of my career.

989
01:04:54.026 --> 01:04:57.737
The Jackson 5
Left Motown Records and went to CBS.

990
01:04:57.905 --> 01:05:00.949
Jermaine stayed behind
because he was married to Hazel

991
01:05:01.284 --> 01:05:03.577
and Hazel was Berry Gordy's daughter.

992
01:05:05.121 --> 01:05:08.123
When my boys left Jermaine back at Motown.

993
01:05:09.125 --> 01:05:11.793
it hurt. because Jermaine wouldn't come.

994
01:05:11.878 --> 01:05:14.713
I don't know if it was upset or angry or
whatever or disappointment or whatever.

995
01:05:14.797 --> 01:05:15.881
Tito Jackson
MICHAEL'S BROTHER

996
01:05:15.965 --> 01:05:19.426
it just was a sad time. that's all.
That's the word. It was sad.

997
01:05:20.136 --> 01:05:24.139
Jermaine felt
that he owed his allegiance to Berry

998
01:05:24.307 --> 01:05:27.142
"cause Berry was the one that gave us our start."

999
01:05:27.894 --> 01:05:29.644
And I felt the same way.

1000
01:05:30.313 --> 01:05:33.982
Berry Gordy maintained the name "Jackson 5"

1001
01:05:34.066 --> 01:05:35.483
and they really thought that maybe

1002
01:05:35.651 --> 01:05:39.404
it wasn't fair that Berry got to keep
the name "Jackson 5."

1003
01:05:39.488 --> 01:05:41.990
so they went to CBS as the Jacksons.

1004
01:05:43.826 --> 01:05:49.831
I was not prepared
for the rubbish that would come my way.

1005
01:05:49.957 --> 01:05:52.751
It was this fear. I guess.

1006
01:05:52.835 --> 01:05:57.255
that what the supposed "lily white" company

1007
01:05:57.340 --> 01:06:00.300
was gonna do to this black family.

1008
01:06:01.761 --> 01:06:04.679
I received phone calls. I received threats.

1009
01:06:05.348 --> 01:06:08.850
There was a lot of prejudice in the business.

1010
01:06:08.976 --> 01:06:15.941
Black records usually had to cross over
from being R&B to pop stations.

1011
01:06:16.150 --> 01:06:19.611
Very rarely did a pop station
just go on a black record.

1012
01:06:19.695 --> 01:06:23.698
It's the most ridiculous thing in the world
when you think of it now

1013
01:06:23.783 --> 01:06:26.034
because it's not like that any more.

1014
01:06:26.118 --> 01:06:28.787
But it sure was in the '60s and '70s.

1015
01:06:29.121 --> 01:06:30.705
Music business was segregated

1016
01:06:30.790 --> 01:06:33.833
and even though the Jackson 5 had crossed over.

1017
01:06:34.543 --> 01:06:37.212
there was just always
this thing that was going on

1018
01:06:37.296 --> 01:06:38.630
that there was a difference

1019
01:06:38.714 --> 01:06:41.383
between R&B and pop.

1020
01:06:41.884 --> 01:06:44.970
Forget the colour. listen to the music.

1021
01:06:45.054 --> 01:06:48.181
Does the music excite your audience?
Yes. Play it.

1022
01:06:57.149 --> 01:07:00.318
Ron Alexenburg called us and asked us

1023
01:07:00.903 --> 01:07:02.654
if we would produce them.

1024
01:07:02.822 --> 01:07:04.990
I wanted to go to proven winners

1025
01:07:05.074 --> 01:07:08.410
and that's why I picked up the phone
and called Kenny Gamble and Leon Huff

1026
01:07:08.744 --> 01:07:11.746
and it was only at that time that I found out
that they were also

1027
01:07:12.206 --> 01:07:14.165
trying to sign the Jacksons and I said.

1028
01:07:14.250 --> 01:07:17.252
"Well. pretend that you signed them
but they're gonna be on Epic Records

1029
01:07:17.378 --> 01:07:19.170
"and please produce them for me."

1030
01:07:22.383 --> 01:07:23.425
That transition

1031
01:07:23.592 --> 01:07:26.094
was a trying time. because

1032
01:07:26.220 --> 01:07:28.847
they had a lot of emotional things
going on with them

1033
01:07:28.931 --> 01:07:33.893
because this was the first time
that Jermaine was not recording with them.

1034
01:07:34.145 --> 01:07:35.186
When Jermaine left.

1035
01:07:35.354 --> 01:07:38.106
Randy came into the group

1036
01:07:38.190 --> 01:07:44.404
and Joe had been preparing Randy.
for a long time. to become a member.

1037
01:07:44.947 --> 01:07:47.699
And he fit in like a glove.

1038
01:07:48.451 --> 01:07:50.326
This here gentleman is Randy Jackson.

1039
01:07:50.411 --> 01:07:51.453
The Jacksons
PHILADELPHIA INT. STUDIO 1977

1040
01:07:51.537 --> 01:07:55.123
and he happens to be the youngest
and the ugliest member of the Jackson 5.

1041
01:07:55.207 --> 01:07:57.917
Now what's the excuse for you. so ugly?

1042
01:07:59.170 --> 01:08:01.880
"Cause I take after my big brother. Tito."

1043
01:08:02.048 --> 01:08:06.092
As soon as we found a recording date
for an artist.

1044
01:08:06.177 --> 01:08:08.344
we would start writing for them

1045
01:08:08.429 --> 01:08:11.222
and not only would Gamble and Huff
write for them.

1046
01:08:11.307 --> 01:08:13.558
but we had McFadden and Whitehead
who wrote for them.

1047
01:08:13.851 --> 01:08:17.604
- All of our writers. all of our staff...
- Dexter. Cynthia Biggs...

1048
01:08:17.688 --> 01:08:19.856
They would know
that the Jacksons were coming in.

1049
01:08:21.859 --> 01:08:24.903
Kenny Gamble and Leon Huff instructed me

1050
01:08:25.112 --> 01:08:26.738
to write a number one for them

1051
01:08:26.822 --> 01:08:30.366
to see if I could come up with any material
that they liked.

1052
01:08:30.451 --> 01:08:31.534
Dexter Wansel
PRODUCER & SONGWRITER

1053
01:08:31.619 --> 01:08:35.580
meaning the Jacksons.
and that Gamble and Huff could approve.

1054
01:08:35.956 --> 01:08:38.166
And so. we would have prepared for them

1055
01:08:39.085 --> 01:08:41.461
maybe 200 songs when they walked in the door.

1056
01:08:41.545 --> 01:08:46.007
And then we'd take those 200 songs
and we'd cut them down to maybe. like. 12.

1057
01:08:46.467 --> 01:08:48.968
The Jacksons themselves were

1058
01:08:49.053 --> 01:08:52.222
interested in moving on with their career.

1059
01:08:52.348 --> 01:08:54.682
They wanted to write. they wanted to produce.

1060
01:08:55.017 --> 01:08:57.644
So Huff and I. we helped them produce.

1061
01:08:57.728 --> 01:09:00.480
Tito was excellent.
"cause he's a great guitar player.

1062
01:09:00.564 --> 01:09:06.027
Kenny Gamble and Leon Huff
was very warm. nice people.

1063
01:09:06.112 --> 01:09:07.403
They had a lot of soul.

1064
01:09:07.947 --> 01:09:09.656
we had a lot in common with the music.

1065
01:09:09.740 --> 01:09:11.116
When I cut their tracks.

1066
01:09:11.242 --> 01:09:13.952
I always included Tito

1067
01:09:14.161 --> 01:09:15.578
in the rhythm section.

1068
01:09:15.663 --> 01:09:20.208
And he told me Motown would not
let him play on their tracks.

1069
01:09:20.417 --> 01:09:22.168
but he played on every one of mine.

1070
01:09:23.921 --> 01:09:28.174
Our studio was running
24 hours a day. so it was like a machine.

1071
01:09:28.509 --> 01:09:29.551
Sometimes.

1072
01:09:29.677 --> 01:09:33.263
we might wanna work until the wee hours

1073
01:09:33.556 --> 01:09:34.639
of the morning.

1074
01:09:34.723 --> 01:09:38.685
Depends on how strong
your creative juices is flowing

1075
01:09:38.853 --> 01:09:40.353
at that moment.

1076
01:09:40.437 --> 01:09:43.231
And the Jacksons were used to curfews.

1077
01:09:44.108 --> 01:09:46.901
But that changed in Philly.

1078
01:09:46.986 --> 01:09:49.404
Well. they were older. they were teenagers then.

1079
01:09:49.488 --> 01:09:52.907
But they were still trying
to induce that old system.

1080
01:09:52.992 --> 01:09:55.785
and Michael rebelled against it.

1081
01:09:56.579 --> 01:09:59.706
Because Michael wanted to hang out

1082
01:10:00.499 --> 01:10:03.960
into the wee hours of the morning. so...
And that's what he did.

1083
01:10:04.253 --> 01:10:07.255
Michael loved his time with Gamble and Huff.

1084
01:10:07.339 --> 01:10:10.133
He really appreciated working with two geniuses

1085
01:10:10.217 --> 01:10:12.427
who wrote so many classic songs.

1086
01:10:12.511 --> 01:10:17.307
Can you tell us. what made you want
to sing in the first place?

1087
01:10:17.391 --> 01:10:18.683
- I don't know.
- You don't know?

1088
01:10:18.767 --> 01:10:21.895
Well. you know how that goes with children.
They just don't know. do they?

1089
01:10:22.104 --> 01:10:24.981
Michael. at that time. was always shy

1090
01:10:25.107 --> 01:10:26.816
and really reserved.

1091
01:10:26.901 --> 01:10:29.611
We would say. "I wanna go get something
to eat." or "Let's do this."

1092
01:10:30.029 --> 01:10:32.447
And he would go. "Okay."

1093
01:10:32.698 --> 01:10:33.990
And he was very humble.

1094
01:10:34.074 --> 01:10:36.618
And I think he was pretty humble
through his life.

1095
01:10:36.702 --> 01:10:40.079
- What's your name?
- Christopher Wansel.

1096
01:10:41.498 --> 01:10:44.042
I was young when that video was made.
I was. like. one or two years old.

1097
01:10:44.126 --> 01:10:45.168
Christopher Wansel
JACKSON FRIEND

1098
01:10:45.252 --> 01:10:47.212
The relationship with the Jacksons started there

1099
01:10:47.296 --> 01:10:48.546
and it continued throughout life.

1100
01:10:48.839 --> 01:10:49.881
Can you sing?

1101
01:10:51.926 --> 01:10:56.137
He can't dance? I wanna see his dance.

1102
01:10:56.222 --> 01:10:59.140
- Come on. man!
- You don't have to.

1103
01:11:00.226 --> 01:11:02.894
I remember a lot of just.

1104
01:11:03.270 --> 01:11:05.980
I guess. excitement and just joy
with those guys at that point. you know.

1105
01:11:06.065 --> 01:11:09.400
"cause a lot of people that would record
would be serious."

1106
01:11:09.485 --> 01:11:11.194
you wouldn't get a smile or anything.

1107
01:11:11.278 --> 01:11:13.196
but these guys were constantly joking
left and right.

1108
01:11:13.489 --> 01:11:15.031
What do you do. booger?

1109
01:11:16.867 --> 01:11:18.785
Well. other than being "the Bishop of Soul"

1110
01:11:18.869 --> 01:11:21.162
I'm also "the Monk of Funk"
and "the High Priest of Rock"

1111
01:11:21.247 --> 01:11:23.206
and "the Bishop of Soul."

1112
01:11:23.415 --> 01:11:25.083
All right!
Who said that?

1113
01:11:25.918 --> 01:11:28.461
I met Michael Jackson
when he first came to Philly

1114
01:11:28.545 --> 01:11:29.587
Billy Paul
ARTIST. PHILADELPHIA INT. RECORDS

1115
01:11:29.797 --> 01:11:31.673
back in. I think. it was 1974.

1116
01:11:32.007 --> 01:11:35.843
He was a very shy. young kid. you know.

1117
01:11:35.928 --> 01:11:38.304
And he was very excited to meet me. you know.

1118
01:11:38.389 --> 01:11:41.891
"cause he... Mrs Jones...
It was at the height of Mrs Jones."

1119
01:11:42.434 --> 01:11:46.020
I welcomed him to the studio and told him
he was gonna enjoy it

1120
01:11:47.273 --> 01:11:50.191
and I'd do a good job. you know.
and he just laughed.

1121
01:11:51.360 --> 01:11:53.569
Michael's voice had changed. obviously.

1122
01:11:53.654 --> 01:11:54.696
from the little boy

1123
01:11:54.780 --> 01:11:58.116
that could hit all those high. piercing.
I'll Be There notes

1124
01:11:58.367 --> 01:12:00.535
to a rawer sound.

1125
01:12:00.619 --> 01:12:02.287
But he was a great singer because

1126
01:12:02.413 --> 01:12:05.456
he studied the great singers.
he wanted to sing like them.

1127
01:12:05.791 --> 01:12:08.835
He knew what he wanted to do with his voice.

1128
01:12:08.919 --> 01:12:12.714
like over-dubbing his voice
and doubling his voice

1129
01:12:12.798 --> 01:12:15.466
and speeding up one voice and this one...

1130
01:12:15.551 --> 01:12:19.721
These are things that he was telling me.
you know. We're the producers.

1131
01:12:19.805 --> 01:12:22.932
He would say.
"Gamble. can I try this? Can I try that?"

1132
01:12:23.017 --> 01:12:25.018
I said. "Yeah. try anything you want."

1133
01:12:26.270 --> 01:12:28.313
- We let him express himself.
- Yeah.

1134
01:12:28.439 --> 01:12:29.480
You know. he was in there

1135
01:12:29.898 --> 01:12:33.109
through the mixes.
he was around me and Huff all the time.

1136
01:12:33.444 --> 01:12:37.572
I remember when they were working
with Gamble and Huff in Philadelphia.

1137
01:12:37.656 --> 01:12:41.367
and I liked their sound and I liked what they
did and they helped them out a lot.

1138
01:12:41.452 --> 01:12:45.038
And that's when
the boys first start writing. too.

1139
01:12:47.416 --> 01:12:50.668
Their first record produced by Gamble and Huff.

1140
01:12:50.753 --> 01:12:51.878
even though it went gold.

1141
01:12:52.254 --> 01:12:55.381
wasn't a really huge album for them.

1142
01:12:55.466 --> 01:12:58.885
It mid-charted in around the 50s

1143
01:12:59.136 --> 01:13:01.512
and he wanted something that was number one.

1144
01:13:03.640 --> 01:13:06.934
When they did their second album. Goin' Places.

1145
01:13:07.770 --> 01:13:09.854
the album was really a flop.

1146
01:13:09.938 --> 01:13:11.147
He was used to selling

1147
01:13:11.273 --> 01:13:14.484
a million or so albums on Motown.

1148
01:13:14.735 --> 01:13:17.153
And he really. in no disrespect to them.

1149
01:13:17.488 --> 01:13:22.992
wanted to produce and write
all his own material.

1150
01:13:23.077 --> 01:13:24.786
He wanted to be in charge.

1151
01:13:26.080 --> 01:13:30.458
Released in 1978 "Destiny" was the
first album produced by the Jacksons.

1152
01:13:30.542 --> 01:13:33.378
When I first heard Destiny.

1153
01:13:33.462 --> 01:13:35.963
I liked it very much.
I was very proud of them.

1154
01:13:36.090 --> 01:13:37.673
I thought they did a real good job.

1155
01:13:40.177 --> 01:13:44.847
The album re-established
The Jacksons as a top selling group.

1156
01:13:50.062 --> 01:13:53.022
He kept reaching for higher plateaus

1157
01:13:53.315 --> 01:13:55.358
and he felt. maybe. that if the group...

1158
01:13:55.484 --> 01:13:56.567
Dennis Edwards
LEAD SINGER."THE TEMPTATIONS"

1159
01:13:56.652 --> 01:13:59.612
Where he wanted to go.
they probably couldn't go with him.

1160
01:13:59.863 --> 01:14:04.826
Michael was beginning
to think of himself as a solo artist

1161
01:14:04.910 --> 01:14:08.579
and I always wondered
what would happen to the brothers

1162
01:14:08.664 --> 01:14:10.081
if Michael left the group.

1163
01:14:10.165 --> 01:14:14.085
Without Michael Jackson. that was gonna be
a tough road for the Jacksons.

1164
01:14:14.169 --> 01:14:15.211
And I also believed

1165
01:14:15.295 --> 01:14:18.256
that that's one of the reasons why
Michael put it off for as long as he could.

1166
01:14:18.590 --> 01:14:19.674
Yeah. I figured he'd go solo.

1167
01:14:19.758 --> 01:14:20.967
Jimmy Ruffin
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

1168
01:14:21.051 --> 01:14:24.554
He was too good.
He couldn't carry his brothers forever.

1169
01:14:27.057 --> 01:14:28.599
One of the lawyers called me in

1170
01:14:28.934 --> 01:14:31.060
and he told me to tell the boys
to save their money

1171
01:14:31.145 --> 01:14:33.354
because Michael is gonna go solo.

1172
01:14:33.439 --> 01:14:35.231
I said. "He can't do that."

1173
01:14:35.315 --> 01:14:37.400
And he said.
"Well. he don't need his brothers."

1174
01:14:38.360 --> 01:14:40.153
I said. "They need one another."

1175
01:14:40.779 --> 01:14:44.115
Joseph just felt that what was really important

1176
01:14:44.199 --> 01:14:46.993
wasn't the individual success of the group

1177
01:14:47.327 --> 01:14:52.248
but it was the group itself
and it was the family itself.

1178
01:14:52.332 --> 01:14:57.670
And that's easy to say
when you're not the lead singer of the group.

1179
01:14:58.297 --> 01:15:02.467
I saw Michael leaving his father as a positive.

1180
01:15:02.551 --> 01:15:05.678
no longer persecuting him. abusing him

1181
01:15:05.971 --> 01:15:10.266
or saying things to him that were ugly.

1182
01:15:10.350 --> 01:15:13.936
He seemed to only be
getting it from one source. his father.

1183
01:15:14.146 --> 01:15:16.981
Michael never felt comfortable
with Joe as his manager.

1184
01:15:17.065 --> 01:15:18.441
"cause he was afraid of him."

1185
01:15:18.525 --> 01:15:21.652
And when you're afraid of somebody.
you don't wanna be around them.

1186
01:15:21.904 --> 01:15:24.655
That was his destiny. to be by himself.

1187
01:15:24.740 --> 01:15:27.033
His confidence level was really high

1188
01:15:27.117 --> 01:15:30.328
and when he made the transition
from us to Quincy.

1189
01:15:30.412 --> 01:15:31.454
he was ready.

1190
01:15:36.084 --> 01:15:38.794
Michael really admired Quincy Jones.

1191
01:15:39.671 --> 01:15:40.838
Because

1192
01:15:41.131 --> 01:15:43.090
Quincy had produced Frank Sinatra.

1193
01:15:45.385 --> 01:15:46.427
Ella Fitzgerald.

1194
01:15:48.305 --> 01:15:49.388
Dinah Washington.

1195
01:15:50.724 --> 01:15:56.354
And so many other acts
during his very illustrious career.

1196
01:15:58.315 --> 01:16:01.526
When he was about to do Off The Wall.
he went to him.

1197
01:16:02.277 --> 01:16:04.195
asking for suggestions

1198
01:16:04.696 --> 01:16:08.783
of people that might be interested
in working with him.

1199
01:16:08.867 --> 01:16:14.121
And the story goes that Quincy Jones said.
"I'm available." and he said.

1200
01:16:14.748 --> 01:16:16.666
"I would love to work with you."

1201
01:16:17.876 --> 01:16:21.546
I was in the studio
for the Off The Wall sessions.

1202
01:16:21.755 --> 01:16:26.217
and so. I was able to actually watch
Michael and Quincy work together.

1203
01:16:26.301 --> 01:16:31.889
And Michael really thought of Quincy
as sort of the father that he hoped

1204
01:16:32.182 --> 01:16:34.267
Joseph could have been for him.

1205
01:16:34.351 --> 01:16:37.144
One of the things that Michael told me
he loved about Working With Quincy

1206
01:16:37.229 --> 01:16:41.107
Was that Quincy thought
Michael's ideas were good ideas.

1207
01:16:41.942 --> 01:16:44.402
And if you listen to some of the demos.

1208
01:16:44.528 --> 01:16:48.239
those songs were complete
When Michael brought them to Quincy.

1209
01:16:48.323 --> 01:16:49.991
I mean. you could have just put them out.

1210
01:16:50.409 --> 01:16:53.744
And Quincy appreciated the fact
that Michael had this amazing ability.

1211
01:16:53.996 --> 01:16:55.454
There was a lot of respect there.

1212
01:16:56.331 --> 01:16:59.667
Quincy Jones has always been
smart about merging what he has to offer

1213
01:16:59.918 --> 01:17:01.127
with what the artist has to offer

1214
01:17:01.211 --> 01:17:03.004
and I think that's probably
one of Quincy's greatest gifts.

1215
01:17:03.088 --> 01:17:04.130
Peabo Bryson
SINGER

1216
01:17:04.214 --> 01:17:06.507
And he certainly did that with Michael
in abundance.

1217
01:17:07.968 --> 01:17:10.970
I will never forget when
he brought Off The Wall over to my house

1218
01:17:11.179 --> 01:17:14.265
to play it for me.

1219
01:17:14.349 --> 01:17:20.688
It just jumped right out of the record player.

1220
01:17:20.772 --> 01:17:26.694
It was the most unbelievable album

1221
01:17:26.778 --> 01:17:28.279
I'd ever heard to that date.

1222
01:17:28.363 --> 01:17:30.656
To me. that's one of the greatest albums
I've ever heard in my life.

1223
01:17:30.741 --> 01:17:32.158
Russell Thompkins. Jr.
LEAD SINGER."THE STYLISTICS"

1224
01:17:32.242 --> 01:17:33.284
When the musicians that I know.

1225
01:17:33.368 --> 01:17:37.913
and we all sit around
and we listen to the arrangements.

1226
01:17:38.373 --> 01:17:41.959
and the production that was done on that
album. the things that Quincy Jones did.

1227
01:17:42.169 --> 01:17:43.294
was fantastic.

1228
01:17:43.420 --> 01:17:45.963
Quincy Jones had horn players
playing such fantastic licks

1229
01:17:46.048 --> 01:17:47.131
Martha Reeves
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

1230
01:17:47.215 --> 01:17:51.093
and had drummers and percussions
that Michael had to dance to.

1231
01:17:51.178 --> 01:17:54.055
and that only made him even the more exciting.

1232
01:17:54.473 --> 01:17:57.683
Quincy was a great arranger.

1233
01:17:57.768 --> 01:18:02.480
Michael was a great singer.
and also had a great foresight

1234
01:18:02.564 --> 01:18:04.857
and it just was a marriage made in heaven.

1235
01:18:06.318 --> 01:18:07.526
I had the pleasure

1236
01:18:07.611 --> 01:18:09.403
of coming up in the same era and watching him

1237
01:18:09.488 --> 01:18:10.529
Eddie Floyd
SINGER & SONGWRITER. STAX RECORDS

1238
01:18:10.614 --> 01:18:13.366
and once he got with Michael... Wow...

1239
01:18:13.575 --> 01:18:15.242
History speaks for itself.

1240
01:18:16.370 --> 01:18:17.495
There was just no way

1241
01:18:17.871 --> 01:18:19.705
that these songs weren't going to be big hits.

1242
01:18:21.958 --> 01:18:24.752
An album would have two very good songs on it

1243
01:18:25.170 --> 01:18:29.131
that they know is gonna be hits.
and then they throw anything on an album.

1244
01:18:29.299 --> 01:18:30.633
to fill it out.

1245
01:18:30.717 --> 01:18:34.679
And he said. "Mother. I don't believe in that.
I think every song should be a hit."

1246
01:18:34.846 --> 01:18:37.973
And so. he just put good songs out there
and gave the people

1247
01:18:38.058 --> 01:18:39.517
good product.

1248
01:18:42.688 --> 01:18:45.981
Actually. it made me start dancing again

1249
01:18:46.066 --> 01:18:47.108
when I went out.

1250
01:18:47.192 --> 01:18:50.945
"cause I was one of those
"I don't wanna sweat" guys.

1251
01:18:51.029 --> 01:18:53.739
When Off The Wall was on.
you had to hit the dance floor.

1252
01:18:53.990 --> 01:18:55.449
It was just absolutely astounding

1253
01:18:55.534 --> 01:18:57.993
and then he just kept getting better and better.

1254
01:18:58.078 --> 01:18:59.120
Abdul "Duke" Fakir
ARTIST."THE FOUR TOPS"

1255
01:19:00.580 --> 01:19:03.791
Such a God-given talent. so precious.

1256
01:19:05.252 --> 01:19:08.295
When he recorded Thriller.
Michael was very excited

1257
01:19:08.422 --> 01:19:09.463
and he said that he thought

1258
01:19:09.589 --> 01:19:12.550
this was going to sell hundreds
and hundreds of millions of copies.

1259
01:19:13.009 --> 01:19:16.429
Quincy kept telling Michael.
"You know what? Maybe five million.

1260
01:19:17.597 --> 01:19:19.640
"I mean. if we do 10 million.
it's gonna be huge.

1261
01:19:19.725 --> 01:19:21.183
"but. you know. don't get your hopes up."

1262
01:19:21.560 --> 01:19:24.228
He was never pleased with what he accomplished.

1263
01:19:24.312 --> 01:19:27.314
He always wanted to accomplish the impossible.

1264
01:19:28.150 --> 01:19:32.987
Michael felt that Quincy
should have been on his team

1265
01:19:33.572 --> 01:19:35.197
with 100 million.

1266
01:19:35.282 --> 01:19:37.366
And he told his attorney.

1267
01:19:37.617 --> 01:19:40.661
"Thriller's not coming out.
Quincy doesn't believe in it.

1268
01:19:40.954 --> 01:19:43.080
"Cancel. The thing's not coming out." right?

1269
01:19:43.999 --> 01:19:46.417
So. Michael had a conversation
with Walter Yetnikoff.

1270
01:19:46.501 --> 01:19:48.586
Who was running CBS at that time.

1271
01:19:48.670 --> 01:19:53.048
And Walter Yetnikoff told Michael.
"Look. who cares what these guys think.

1272
01:19:53.133 --> 01:19:57.011
"It's not about what their impression is
of this music.

1273
01:19:57.095 --> 01:19:59.054
"it's what you believe to be the case.

1274
01:19:59.139 --> 01:20:01.056
"And if you believe this is
going to sell 100 million copies.

1275
01:20:01.141 --> 01:20:02.183
"guess what. Michael?

1276
01:20:02.309 --> 01:20:03.517
"I'm with you.

1277
01:20:03.602 --> 01:20:07.521
"Let this thing come out.
Don't mess with this. Just let it come out."

1278
01:20:07.647 --> 01:20:08.689
And then Michael did.

1279
01:20:09.024 --> 01:20:10.483
But it could have gone either way.

1280
01:20:10.692 --> 01:20:16.530
We were averaging a million units a week.
which no other record had done.

1281
01:20:16.615 --> 01:20:17.656
Frank Dileo
JACKSON'S MANAGER 1984-89. 2009

1282
01:20:20.994 --> 01:20:26.248
Michael Jackson. that year with Thriller.
saved the record business.

1283
01:20:26.333 --> 01:20:28.459
Tower Records was going out of business.

1284
01:20:28.710 --> 01:20:34.882
CBS itself had had two black Fridays
where they laid off. like. a thousand people.

1285
01:20:34.966 --> 01:20:39.845
other companies were laying off people.
Everybody was losing their job.

1286
01:20:39.930 --> 01:20:41.889
But Thriller was so big.

1287
01:20:42.682 --> 01:20:47.520
it brought millions of people into the stores

1288
01:20:47.979 --> 01:20:51.690
and they not only bought Thriller.
they bought other product.

1289
01:20:51.900 --> 01:20:56.195
It was the music that will probably
influence contemporary artists

1290
01:20:56.279 --> 01:20:58.823
for a long. long time to come.

1291
01:20:58.907 --> 01:21:03.369
It gave us a...

1292
01:21:03.453 --> 01:21:06.997
A goal. a bull's-eye or a dream to get to.

1293
01:21:07.290 --> 01:21:08.791
something to aspire to.

1294
01:21:09.543 --> 01:21:12.795
After Michael made Off The Wall.
and then Thriller.

1295
01:21:13.296 --> 01:21:18.217
I knew then that it was like shooting a rocket
up to the moon.

1296
01:21:21.888 --> 01:21:23.264
Were you aware of the sales?

1297
01:21:23.598 --> 01:21:26.433
I pretty much did the album
and just sat back and watched.

1298
01:21:27.435 --> 01:21:28.686
He saw where he wanted to go

1299
01:21:28.770 --> 01:21:29.812
Freda Payne
SINGER

1300
01:21:29.938 --> 01:21:31.063
and he went there.

1301
01:21:31.398 --> 01:21:32.481
And nobody could stop him.

1302
01:21:36.778 --> 01:21:38.737
He went to a level

1303
01:21:38.989 --> 01:21:41.031
that only the very great have obtained.

1304
01:21:45.120 --> 01:21:47.288
He wanted to be the best and he was the best.

1305
01:21:52.002 --> 01:21:54.628
God took that little man and he says.

1306
01:21:55.005 --> 01:21:57.381
"Okay now. you take over the music world."

1307
01:21:57.465 --> 01:21:58.507
Bobby Taylor
ARTIST. GORDY & MOTOWN RECORDS

1308
01:21:58.675 --> 01:21:59.967
"It now belongs to you."

1309
01:22:02.637 --> 01:22:04.763
What made him so special

1310
01:22:05.181 --> 01:22:06.891
is that he was held back

1311
01:22:07.475 --> 01:22:08.767
for so long

1312
01:22:08.852 --> 01:22:11.812
that when he was finally released.
all of it came out.

1313
01:22:13.231 --> 01:22:15.316
He just lit the stage on fire.

1314
01:22:15.734 --> 01:22:18.944
He stole the show from everybody.
including the Jackson 5.

1315
01:22:19.029 --> 01:22:20.070
Tito Jackson
MICHAEL'S BROTHER

1316
01:22:21.573 --> 01:22:23.282
Michael was into his fans.

1317
01:22:23.909 --> 01:22:26.660
To make all these people that happy.
it charged him up. it really did.

1318
01:22:26.745 --> 01:22:27.953
Ronnie Rancifer
KEYBOARDIST."JACKSON 5" 1967-77

1319
01:22:30.498 --> 01:22:34.126
My fondest memory is the Motown 25.

1320
01:22:34.210 --> 01:22:36.337
Yeah.
We were on that show.

1321
01:22:36.421 --> 01:22:37.463
- and he premiered the moonwalk. Wow.
- That was something.

1322
01:22:37.547 --> 01:22:38.589
Valerie Simpson & Nickolas Ashford.

1323
01:22:38.673 --> 01:22:39.715
SINGERS & SONGWRITERS.
"ASHFORD & SIMPSON"

1324
01:22:43.595 --> 01:22:44.637
Michael called me

1325
01:22:45.138 --> 01:22:48.015
when he got home from doing Motown 25.

1326
01:22:48.099 --> 01:22:49.558
and said. "I've just given
the greatest performance of my life."

1327
01:22:49.643 --> 01:22:50.684
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

1328
01:22:55.231 --> 01:22:57.858
How excited we all were for him.

1329
01:22:58.234 --> 01:23:01.070
it was like. "I guess I've arrived." you know?

1330
01:23:01.154 --> 01:23:03.614
Dionne Warwick
SINGER

1331
01:23:03.740 --> 01:23:06.575
With an armful of Grammys.
It was wonderful.

1332
01:23:07.494 --> 01:23:10.621
In 1984 Michael won an unprecedented
8 Grammys for"Thriller'.

1333
01:23:14.668 --> 01:23:18.128
"Thriller" became the best selling album
of all time with sales exceeding 110 million.

1334
01:23:19.631 --> 01:23:20.673
Michael!

1335
01:23:22.133 --> 01:23:25.469
During the eighties Michael had more
number 1 hits than any other artist.

1336
01:23:30.850 --> 01:23:32.476
Michael Jackson is

1337
01:23:32.686 --> 01:23:36.021
one of the greatest artists of all time.

1338
01:23:36.106 --> 01:23:40.651
who transcended being labeled
black. white. red. yellow.

1339
01:23:40.735 --> 01:23:45.072
it didn't matter.
he appealed to everybody. everywhere.

1340
01:23:45.448 --> 01:23:51.036
I think he came here ready
"cause he always wanted to be a superstar.

1341
01:23:51.121 --> 01:23:55.916
He was wearing little rings on his fingers
when he was a little man. you know.

1342
01:23:56.543 --> 01:23:58.335
He was very conscious

1343
01:23:58.753 --> 01:24:00.921
of the iconoclastic nature of "Michael Jackson."

1344
01:24:01.006 --> 01:24:02.047
J. Randy Taraborrelli
JACKSON FRIEND AND BIOGRAPHER

1345
01:24:03.341 --> 01:24:05.634
and what it would mean historically.

1346
01:24:05.969 --> 01:24:07.928
Michael's image was very important to him

1347
01:24:08.054 --> 01:24:10.431
because Fred Astaire
and the people that he studied.

1348
01:24:10.849 --> 01:24:13.058
Jackie Wilson. James Brown...

1349
01:24:13.226 --> 01:24:17.271
How are they being revered? Why are they
so terrific and what did they do?

1350
01:24:17.355 --> 01:24:18.397
And he was a great student.

1351
01:24:18.481 --> 01:24:19.940
Ron Alexenburg
SNR. VICE PRESIDENT CBS & EPIC RECORDS

1352
01:24:20.025 --> 01:24:21.358
It just didn't come upon him.

1353
01:24:21.443 --> 01:24:23.819
he studied his craft. he worked at it.

1354
01:24:24.195 --> 01:24:25.988
He was directing his career.

1355
01:24:26.489 --> 01:24:29.366
he was so street smart

1356
01:24:29.451 --> 01:24:35.664
and he knew how to make a campaign work.
and more importantly. how to make it last.

1357
01:24:35.999 --> 01:24:39.835
He believed that the biggest stars
left the biggest impression

1358
01:24:39.919 --> 01:24:42.629
and it was bigger than just their art. you know.

1359
01:24:42.714 --> 01:24:45.299
What you thought of instantly

1360
01:24:45.842 --> 01:24:47.676
when you thought of these celebrities

1361
01:24:47.761 --> 01:24:50.512
and with Michael.
what you began to think of instantly

1362
01:24:50.597 --> 01:24:53.140
was the fedora hat. it was the one glove.

1363
01:24:53.725 --> 01:24:57.352
On the show that we did together
at Madison Square Garden.

1364
01:24:57.437 --> 01:24:59.313
he came out with a suitcase

1365
01:24:59.773 --> 01:25:03.817
and inside was the glove. and he had the hat.

1366
01:25:04.986 --> 01:25:09.073
and he had everything he needed to show them.

1367
01:25:09.157 --> 01:25:12.451
"Nobody does it better than I
and these are my trademarks."

1368
01:25:12.911 --> 01:25:16.538
The total package
of Michael Jackson became very important.

1369
01:25:16.623 --> 01:25:19.374
especially with the advent of video culture.

1370
01:25:19.542 --> 01:25:21.835
which happened at the exact same time

1371
01:25:21.920 --> 01:25:24.630
that Billie Jean and Beat It
were becoming hit records.

1372
01:25:26.299 --> 01:25:31.053
"Billie Jean" was the 1st video by a black
artist to receive heavy rotation on MTV.

1373
01:25:34.265 --> 01:25:37.893
Michael never officially left The Jacksons.
"Victory" (1984) was their last album together.

1374
01:25:43.441 --> 01:25:48.362
It was an immense pressure
to be in the public eye

1375
01:25:48.446 --> 01:25:51.448
and he kept wanting to look better and better.

1376
01:25:51.866 --> 01:25:54.243
He was very. very self-conscious.

1377
01:25:54.369 --> 01:25:57.329
Michael felt under pressure

1378
01:25:57.455 --> 01:26:00.290
where his image was concerned

1379
01:26:00.792 --> 01:26:02.000
because of who he is.

1380
01:26:02.085 --> 01:26:05.879
He was a black guy. he was an inner-city guy.

1381
01:26:05.964 --> 01:26:08.507
How could he be the darling of white society?

1382
01:26:09.217 --> 01:26:10.467
He had to change.

1383
01:26:12.303 --> 01:26:18.475
I think all that was what led
to the first plastic surgery. in 1978.

1384
01:26:18.685 --> 01:26:20.853
I went to interview Michael
at his home in Encino

1385
01:26:20.937 --> 01:26:23.564
and he showed up at the door
with bandages on his face

1386
01:26:23.648 --> 01:26:25.315
and his eyes were black and blue.

1387
01:26:25.400 --> 01:26:27.693
and I thought that he had been
in some kind of a fight.

1388
01:26:29.028 --> 01:26:32.865
He explained to me that he had fallen on stage

1389
01:26:33.408 --> 01:26:34.992
and broke his nose.

1390
01:26:35.076 --> 01:26:37.786
This was why he had that first surgery.

1391
01:26:39.998 --> 01:26:43.000
His next major one was in 1981

1392
01:26:43.084 --> 01:26:45.919
and he stayed with me for four weeks.
I took care of him.

1393
01:26:46.462 --> 01:26:50.299
I always felt that he looked so good
after that second one.

1394
01:26:50.383 --> 01:26:51.717
he never needed to do more.

1395
01:26:52.343 --> 01:26:53.552
And then after that.

1396
01:26:53.636 --> 01:26:55.721
there were all kinds of other things
that were going on

1397
01:26:55.805 --> 01:26:58.265
that it was really hard to determine.

1398
01:26:58.933 --> 01:27:01.185
you know. what he was doing
and when he was doing it.

1399
01:27:09.194 --> 01:27:11.612
I think he should have stopped
before he did. yes.

1400
01:27:11.696 --> 01:27:15.282
Being vulnerable and listening to others.
he just kept going.

1401
01:27:15.366 --> 01:27:16.408
Rebbie Jackson
MICHAEL'S SISTER

1402
01:27:16.868 --> 01:27:20.621
Steve Hoefflin. I believe.
and ll said to Michael.

1403
01:27:20.705 --> 01:27:27.461
did too many operations
and made Michael not secure. but insecure.

1404
01:27:27.795 --> 01:27:31.506
One of the ways Steve stayed close to Michael

1405
01:27:31.591 --> 01:27:35.052
was constantly telling him what he needed.

1406
01:27:35.136 --> 01:27:39.556
Steve would probably disagree with that.
